WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.040
[Amit Varma]: My guest in the episode today once said something that reveals the power of popular culture.

00:00:11.040 --> 00:00:16.280
[Amit Varma]: In his younger days, in the 1990s, he spoke about how he once watched a film on a Friday

00:00:16.280 --> 00:00:21.360
[Amit Varma]: in which a character played by Renuka Shahane died. He was so disturbed by it that he waited

00:00:21.360 --> 00:00:26.000
[Amit Varma]: until that Monday for a show called Surabhi to air on television so that he could see

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:30.960
[Amit Varma]: Shahane alive again. He said he had tears in his eyes. This, to me, is not a random

00:00:30.960 --> 00:00:36.680
[Amit Varma]: cheesy story about a young person, but a reflection of how much stories matter to all of us, and

00:00:36.680 --> 00:00:42.160
[Amit Varma]: the emotional resonance of culture. Films and music and books are not just entertainment

00:00:42.160 --> 00:00:46.840
[Amit Varma]: and escape. They provide us with the backdrop of our dreams, the soundtrack of our lives,

00:00:46.840 --> 00:00:51.480
[Amit Varma]: and sometimes even the backbone of our existence. They help us make sense of the world even

00:00:51.480 --> 00:00:55.120
[Amit Varma]: when little of sense seems to be happening in it. They help us make sense of our own

00:00:55.120 --> 00:01:00.560
[Amit Varma]: selves through the lives of others. This is why the importance of art is highest in the

00:01:00.560 --> 00:01:05.720
[Amit Varma]: darkest of times. As my guest said once, the worst time to be an artist may just be the

00:01:05.720 --> 00:01:27.280
[Amit Varma]: best time to be an artist. Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen. My guest today is Varun

00:01:27.280 --> 00:01:31.960
[Amit Varma]: Grover, writer, screenwriter, lyricist, comedian, filmmaker, in fact, so many things that it

00:01:31.960 --> 00:01:36.560
[Amit Varma]: feels reductive to try and spell them all out. I've been a fan of both Varun's work

00:01:36.560 --> 00:01:40.800
[Amit Varma]: and his fearlessness for many years now, and we've been talking about doing this episode

00:01:40.800 --> 00:01:45.000
[Amit Varma]: for a while. I'm so glad we finally made it happen in an eventful recording that faced

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:49.560
[Amit Varma]: a few disruptions, though thankfully, nothing from the state. At one point, we interrupted

00:01:49.560 --> 00:01:53.960
[Amit Varma]: the recording because of a large fire we could see from the window of my home studio, and

00:01:53.960 --> 00:01:57.880
[Amit Varma]: we lost a little bit of audio near the start because of which my early question about the

00:01:57.880 --> 00:02:02.680
[Amit Varma]: media might feel a bit abrupt. But I loved the conversation I had. We had so much fun

00:02:02.680 --> 00:02:07.240
[Amit Varma]: rambling here and there as the hours went by that we forgot to discuss some of the key

00:02:07.240 --> 00:02:12.200
[Amit Varma]: things I wanted to discuss with Varun, such as the craft of comedy and writing lyrics.

00:02:12.200 --> 00:02:16.920
[Amit Varma]: At which point, you might ask, ki phir baat kya kya? Well, you'll have to listen to find

00:02:16.920 --> 00:02:21.600
[Amit Varma]: out we had a blast. Before we start, a public service announcement. Registration is open

00:02:21.600 --> 00:02:26.000
[Amit Varma]: for the September cohort of my writing course, The Art of Clear Writing. The course kicks

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:31.120
[Amit Varma]: off on Saturday, September 10. And you can go to indiauncut.com slash clear writing to

00:02:31.120 --> 00:02:35.920
[Amit Varma]: register. And now let's go to a unique kind of commercial break. Capital Gyaan by Deepak

00:02:35.920 --> 00:02:41.320
[Amit Varma]: Chinnoy. This is like a show within a commercial from the kind sponsors of this episode, Capital

00:02:41.320 --> 00:02:56.200
[Unknown]: Mind. Did you know that Indian equity markets make more money when they're closed than when

00:02:56.200 --> 00:03:00.600
[Unknown]: they're open? More than 90% of the nifty and sensex returns since 2009 have happened overnight

00:03:00.600 --> 00:03:06.840
[Unknown]: between 3.30pm and 9am when the markets are asleep. Every crazy event makes you want to

00:03:06.840 --> 00:03:11.960
[Unknown]: respond to tweak your investments and it never seems to be enough. If you want to grow your

00:03:11.960 --> 00:03:17.280
[Unknown]: money, you have to let some of it sleep through the madness of everyday life. Deciding not

00:03:17.280 --> 00:03:22.680
[Unknown]: to react can often be the best action you can take. Talk to us and let us make the right

00:03:22.680 --> 00:03:28.160
[Unknown]: decisions for you so you don't have to. I'm Deepak Chinnoy, CEO at Capital Mind. Take

00:03:28.160 --> 00:03:34.840
[Unknown]: a look at our portfolio management service at cm.social slash seen unseen. Worry less

00:03:34.840 --> 00:03:43.000
[Unknown]: about your money and make it work for you. That's cm.social slash seen unseen. Hey, I

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:48.960
[Amit Varma]: want to repeat that URL cm.social slash seen unseen. Deepak has been a guest on my podcast

00:03:48.960 --> 00:03:56.360
[Amit Varma]: and he handles my money as well. My actions are the best endorsement. Varun, welcome to

00:03:56.360 --> 00:04:01.880
[Guest]: the scene in the unseen. Ji shukriya, bohot time se sun rahe hain and I've been a huge

00:04:01.880 --> 00:04:10.160
[Guest]: fan of India Uncut. One of one of those early Indian, I would say success stories in the

00:04:10.160 --> 00:04:17.440
[Guest]: internet space. And I was almost a fanboy. I would say almost because I've always been

00:04:17.440 --> 00:04:24.680
[Guest]: aware about the idea of being fanboys is slightly problematic. But I still I was constantly

00:04:24.680 --> 00:04:31.960
[Guest]: always following waiting for new, you know, posts on on India Uncut or one of the high

00:04:31.960 --> 00:04:41.000
[Guest]: points of my blogging life was that at one point, India Uncut had linked a story on my

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:48.960
[Guest]: satire blog and it got lots of traffic. So it's it's been whatever I think 16 years since

00:04:48.960 --> 00:04:55.680
[Guest]: that happened, probably might have happened in 2005 or 2006. And this is the first time

00:04:55.680 --> 00:05:00.480
[Guest]: we are actually talking. So it's, it's a it's a bit of a landmark for me.

00:05:00.480 --> 00:05:04.920
[Amit Varma]: Well, thank you. That's so kind of you. And I should say it's a landmark for me because

00:05:04.920 --> 00:05:10.080
[Amit Varma]: I've admired your work all these years as well, not just your work per se, but also

00:05:10.080 --> 00:05:14.280
[Amit Varma]: the breadth of your work. So I have a question which I think applies to in a sense both the

00:05:14.280 --> 00:05:19.720
[Amit Varma]: media and the arts, which is that if you sort of look at the media, you can look at it in

00:05:19.720 --> 00:05:25.960
[Amit Varma]: two ways. One way is that the media is fulfilling supply and demand, people want information,

00:05:25.960 --> 00:05:31.720
[Amit Varma]: people want narratives, media fulfills that demand, jab tak profitable hai, chalte raho,

00:05:31.720 --> 00:05:35.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, where do the salaries come from, the bottom line is important, and so on and

00:05:35.920 --> 00:05:41.000
[Amit Varma]: so forth. That is the imperative and that is the justification a lot of people will

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:45.400
[Amit Varma]: give you. Other people like I think you and me would believe that there is something higher

00:05:45.400 --> 00:05:50.360
[Amit Varma]: there. You know, you can get into the cliches of afflicting the comfortable, comforting

00:05:50.360 --> 00:05:54.160
[Amit Varma]: the afflicted or we can talk about speaking truth to power, first draft of history, blah,

00:05:54.160 --> 00:05:58.300
[Amit Varma]: blah, blah. Leaving the cliches aside, there is this sense we have that there is something

00:05:58.300 --> 00:06:03.960
[Amit Varma]: more that we don't follow that demand, but we shape it in a certain way that there are

00:06:03.960 --> 00:06:09.880
[Amit Varma]: certain things we have to cover certain things we have to write about. And this almost seems

00:06:09.880 --> 00:06:15.480
[Amit Varma]: like a binary, it's it's hard to sort of find a continuum between them or find a compromise

00:06:15.480 --> 00:06:20.760
[Amit Varma]: ground. And what we see what I see in the media is that, you know, there is that old

00:06:20.760 --> 00:06:24.800
[Amit Varma]: saying from rock, if you ain't got nothing, you got nothing to lose. And it's the same

00:06:24.800 --> 00:06:29.880
[Amit Varma]: thing that your big media houses will, you know, kowtow before the powers the most because

00:06:29.880 --> 00:06:34.300
[Amit Varma]: they have the most to lose. You could be running a daily newspaper, but the group that owns

00:06:34.300 --> 00:06:38.360
[Amit Varma]: you also as a chemical factory, wahan pe IT raid ho jayegi, blah, blah, blah, you have

00:06:38.360 --> 00:06:43.080
[Amit Varma]: so much to lose that those guys basically follow the imperatives of the first sort with

00:06:43.080 --> 00:06:49.400
[Amit Varma]: just to survive, they have to crawl, as it were, whereas the fighters that you see people

00:06:49.400 --> 00:06:54.800
[Amit Varma]: like alt news and scroll and wire and news minute and so on. They are much smaller operations

00:06:54.800 --> 00:07:00.400
[Amit Varma]: and independent operations. And they are of course, full of brave people, risking a lot

00:07:00.400 --> 00:07:06.440
[Amit Varma]: personally, but at the same time, in terms of what there is to lose, there is not so

00:07:06.440 --> 00:07:11.200
[Amit Varma]: much old money behind that. And all of that you look at alt news, what Prateek and Zubair

00:07:11.200 --> 00:07:15.680
[Amit Varma]: do, it's basically a labor of love, you know, jab tak chalega chalega after that it is what

00:07:15.680 --> 00:07:21.400
[Amit Varma]: it is, it's a labor of love and people recognize it as such. So this makes me sort of wonder

00:07:21.400 --> 00:07:26.040
[Amit Varma]: about which side of the line do we come down on, you know, and and the same question would

00:07:26.040 --> 00:07:32.200
[Amit Varma]: really apply to the arts, because arts me bhi wahi funda hai that if I am an OTT platform,

00:07:32.200 --> 00:07:37.200
[Amit Varma]: the logical thing for me would not be to have political content in there, not take pangas

00:07:37.200 --> 00:07:43.120
[Amit Varma]: in any way. I was rewatching Masaan yesterday and I started on Hotstar. And Hotstar pe poora

00:07:43.120 --> 00:07:48.680
[Guest]: scene kaat diya, like you know about that, right? Das minute kaat diya usme se, shurume.

00:07:48.680 --> 00:07:54.280
[Amit Varma]: The bedroom scene. And I managed to, I said then forget it, I'll just watch it on Netflix.

00:07:54.280 --> 00:07:59.240
[Amit Varma]: Now according to Google, your runtime is 1 hour 49 minutes, Hotstar pe 1 hour 36 sa.

00:07:59.240 --> 00:08:05.240
[Amit Varma]: Ispe bhi Netflix pe 1 hour 46 tha, toh 3 minute kahin gaye, pata nahi kaha gaye. But from

00:08:05.240 --> 00:08:10.040
[Amit Varma]: what I remember, I couldn't figure out kya kaata hai. But so the thing is, you understand

00:08:10.040 --> 00:08:14.800
[Amit Varma]: the imperatives of some of these big guys. But at the same time, you have independent

00:08:14.800 --> 00:08:19.920
[Amit Varma]: artists saying ki nahi mujhe jo karna hai, karenge. And those voices will always be from

00:08:19.920 --> 00:08:24.120
[Amit Varma]: the margins, no mainstream house is going to take off. And simultaneously, to add a

00:08:24.120 --> 00:08:28.120
[Amit Varma]: different theme to that, we're living in an age where I think the mainstream is dissipating.

00:08:28.120 --> 00:08:32.760
[Amit Varma]: More and more creators like us have the tools of production at our hands, we can make whatever

00:08:32.760 --> 00:08:36.400
[Amit Varma]: we want, put it out, we don't have to go through gatekeepers, we don't have to worry about

00:08:36.400 --> 00:08:42.720
[Amit Varma]: these other imperatives. So what are your thoughts on the trade offs involved here?

00:08:42.720 --> 00:08:47.760
[Amit Varma]: Because the rational line that many of the big media houses would take that a Netflix

00:08:47.760 --> 00:08:51.520
[Amit Varma]: or a Hotstar would take that boss, we have to survive, panga kyu lene ka, there is too

00:08:51.520 --> 00:08:57.600
[Amit Varma]: much to lose, you know, for 1% of the art, why should we put 99% at risk? That's a rational

00:08:57.600 --> 00:09:04.760
[Amit Varma]: line. But at the same time, you know, that 1% is the most important.

00:09:04.760 --> 00:09:14.080
[Guest]: So mera yeh maana hai ki news media jo hai khas karke, the two kind of categories you

00:09:14.080 --> 00:09:18.720
[Guest]: mentioned, one is the big media houses who have a lot to lose. And that's why we are

00:09:18.720 --> 00:09:25.960
[Guest]: kind of, they are kind of crawling and all that. But I think usse zyada kuch yaha ho

00:09:25.960 --> 00:09:35.360
[Guest]: raha hai, abhi jo ho raha hai. We can't compare this thing to the emergency where I would

00:09:35.360 --> 00:09:45.280
[Guest]: say ki media ko pata tha sahi aur galat kya hai, aur wo because of the political pressure

00:09:45.280 --> 00:09:50.400
[Guest]: and because of whatever the gains they had to make, they were choosing the wrong. This

00:09:50.400 --> 00:09:56.240
[Guest]: time, I think the distinction is gone. They don't really know what is right or what is

00:09:56.240 --> 00:10:00.840
[Guest]: wrong. They're not deliberately choosing the wrong. They are actually choosing the right,

00:10:00.840 --> 00:10:09.080
[Guest]: what they think is right. So it's not like they are being pressurized into doing something.

00:10:09.080 --> 00:10:13.680
[Guest]: I think that's what they always wanted to do. That's the thing. And this time there

00:10:13.680 --> 00:10:21.720
[Guest]: is, so it's like win-win. Wo karna bhi wohi chahate the. Usi tare ka zahar phailana, usi

00:10:21.720 --> 00:10:30.320
[Guest]: tare ka divisiveness. Divisiveness is the outcome of what they are doing. But the statements

00:10:30.320 --> 00:10:36.960
[Guest]: or the line they are choosing or the news they are trying or, you know, the overall

00:10:36.960 --> 00:10:44.440
[Guest]: agenda of the news right now completely aligns with, I would say, most of the anchors who

00:10:44.440 --> 00:10:50.000
[Guest]: are delivering that news or most of the reporters who are reporting or most of the houses that

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:57.240
[Guest]: are, you know, the big moneybags who are running these channels. So it's slightly different

00:10:57.240 --> 00:11:02.160
[Guest]: from isliye is baar woh bhi nahi hai ki we can't say they were asked to bend and they

00:11:02.160 --> 00:11:10.520
[Guest]: crawled and all. No one actually had to even ask this time. This is a very natural allyship

00:11:10.520 --> 00:11:16.520
[Guest]: in a way, what is happening and what we are seeing. And that's why it's not like ki ye

00:11:16.520 --> 00:11:23.640
[Guest]: badal jaayega agar sarkaar badli jo ki, matlab, anyway, I don't know, woh kab hone wala hai

00:11:23.640 --> 00:11:34.880
[Guest]: ki nahi. It's slightly different. And exactly so, jo aapne bola jo ki, kuch log jo fight

00:11:34.880 --> 00:11:42.040
[Guest]: back kar rahe hain, Alt News and News Minute and Wire and Scroll and many other independent

00:11:42.040 --> 00:11:51.920
[Guest]: whatever, journalists and fact checkers. Again, they are not, you know, they are not doing

00:11:51.920 --> 00:11:58.560
[Guest]: it because they have nothing to lose. Of course, all of us have something to lose. So dono

00:11:58.560 --> 00:12:06.460
[Guest]: taraf is samay jo bhi ho raha hai, woh bahut core belief ke saath ho raha hai. We believe

00:12:06.460 --> 00:12:12.960
[Guest]: in certain things and that's why we are doing this, whatever we are doing. So that I think

00:12:12.960 --> 00:12:19.160
[Guest]: is a major, whatever, departure from what emergency was or what generally how we see

00:12:19.160 --> 00:12:25.200
[Guest]: the world over when, you know, when certain regimes kind of pressurize the media to behave

00:12:25.200 --> 00:12:32.800
[Guest]: a certain way and they do. This time I think it is a, it is a, it is quite a natural allyship.

00:12:32.800 --> 00:12:39.960
[Guest]: Toh woh hai. Lekin haan, uske baad aapka jo doosra sawal tha, which was about the arts

00:12:39.960 --> 00:12:50.200
[Guest]: and which is also in a way related ki, film jo censor karke aa jaati hai ya bahut saari

00:12:50.200 --> 00:12:57.440
[Guest]: cheezon mein censorship, arts mein, cinema mein ho rahi hai. Waha pe, yes, in some of

00:12:57.440 --> 00:13:09.400
[Guest]: the cases it is because of the people at the helm in various media organizations which

00:13:09.400 --> 00:13:19.080
[Guest]: are, let's say, the art-based, this thing. Toh waha pe, shayad yeh na ho ki woh, naturally

00:13:19.080 --> 00:13:23.020
[Guest]: woh chahate hoon ki, haan, isko censorship kar diya jaye. But yeah, so they are choosing

00:13:23.020 --> 00:13:33.880
[Guest]: the path of least resistance and maximum profits. Aur woh, woh bhi kaafi, manna woh ek bahut

00:13:33.880 --> 00:13:43.800
[Guest]: purana system hai, jo ki, as, I don't know, have you seen this film called The Network?

00:13:43.800 --> 00:13:48.520
[Amit Varma]: Network 1976. 70s ka film. I saw it as a kid, Peter Finch and all that, right? I saw it

00:13:48.520 --> 00:13:54.200
[Guest]: as a kid, I don't remember. Yeah, so usme ek scene hai, usme, there is a news anchor

00:13:54.200 --> 00:14:00.560
[Guest]: who because of some traumatic event, he comes, he is fired from his channel but then he comes

00:14:00.560 --> 00:14:07.560
[Guest]: back and he starts delivering a very rousing lecture on TV about, if you're angry and,

00:14:07.560 --> 00:14:13.160
[Guest]: you know, just open your windows and scream that I'm done, I'm done with it and all that.

00:14:13.160 --> 00:14:19.840
[Guest]: I don't remember the exact line. And that guy becomes a cult in its own self. Aur woh

00:14:19.840 --> 00:14:24.960
[Guest]: ek tarah ki cult bana leta hai, TV, kyunki woh achanak se woh us tarah ki ek harkat TV

00:14:24.960 --> 00:14:31.440
[Guest]: pe karta hai ki woh bahut TRP aa jata hai, toh usko wapas TV pe laana padta hai un logon

00:14:31.440 --> 00:14:42.560
[Guest]: ko. Toh I think Simon Beale, his name was in the film. And then that cult starts growing

00:14:42.560 --> 00:14:48.600
[Guest]: and channels are kind of, the channel is making profits because of that show getting lots

00:14:48.600 --> 00:14:57.160
[Guest]: of TRPs and it's almost like, it's a mix of what I would say, Kiran Bedi ki Adalat meets

00:14:57.160 --> 00:15:05.120
[Guest]: one of those angry anchors jo bolta hai ki chayan se sona hai toh jaag jao and all that,

00:15:05.120 --> 00:15:13.680
[Guest]: meets Arnab Goswami in many ways where it's just unbridled rage on TV and people just

00:15:13.680 --> 00:15:21.600
[Guest]: love watching that kind of rage, someone going completely unhinged on TV. So, teen chaar

00:15:21.600 --> 00:15:28.640
[Guest]: cheezon ka and extreme righteousness which flows through this guy. Toh chaar paan cheeze

00:15:28.640 --> 00:15:37.880
[Guest]: hoti hai and then at some point in the arc, his speeches become about actually bringing

00:15:37.880 --> 00:15:44.320
[Guest]: down capitalism and bringing down this big channel he's part of. And then he's brought

00:15:44.320 --> 00:15:51.440
[Guest]: to a meeting with the channel boss and the network boss actually who has many, many channels

00:15:51.440 --> 00:15:57.400
[Guest]: under them and other stuff also. And then this guy gets him into a huge room and there's

00:15:57.400 --> 00:16:03.960
[Guest]: a huge table which is like probably 100 seater kind of a table. Toh uske ek edge pe wo boss

00:16:03.960 --> 00:16:09.480
[Guest]: khada hota hai aur ek edge pe isko bithata hai. And then he gives him this speech about

00:16:09.480 --> 00:16:18.800
[Guest]: basically, apna muh band rakho because there are no countries, there are no nations, there

00:16:18.800 --> 00:16:26.960
[Guest]: are no people, there is only one thing which is business, which is money. So, he gives

00:16:26.960 --> 00:16:33.800
[Guest]: him that basically almost the basics of our existence in this century and previous one

00:16:33.800 --> 00:16:41.480
[Guest]: I think. Toh wo sabse bada sach hai jo hamesha se raha hai ki kuch bhi nahi hai. Yeh jo hum

00:16:41.480 --> 00:16:46.040
[Guest]: theek hai, hum har cheez choti, badi, bahut cheezon ko leke hum log ladte hain. Aur wo

00:16:46.040 --> 00:16:53.520
[Guest]: caste bhi hai, aur wo religion bhi hai, aur wo nationality bhi hai. Kai baar log Mohamad

00:16:53.520 --> 00:16:57.720
[Guest]: Rafi aur Kishore Kumar ko leke bhi lad jaate hain. Wo utne bhi camps bane hue hain bahut

00:16:57.720 --> 00:17:07.120
[Guest]: leke. But ultimately what this guy says and what I think is the truth of our modern societies,

00:17:07.120 --> 00:17:16.440
[Guest]: everything is ultimately money and that's also one of the reasons why I think lots of

00:17:16.440 --> 00:17:23.360
[Guest]: decisions by the media right now are, you know, kind of justified with that even if

00:17:23.360 --> 00:17:29.160
[Guest]: no matter how horrible. Some of these people, I'm sure, have conscience. Are not like completely,

00:17:29.160 --> 00:17:33.760
[Guest]: you know, aisa nahi hai ki wo subhe jab card swipe karte hain andar jaane ke liye toh unki

00:17:33.760 --> 00:17:39.360
[Guest]: aatma wahan chali jaate hain andar. Aatma leke jaate hunge andar. But they justified by that

00:17:39.360 --> 00:17:50.560
[Guest]: thing. So, they have been kind of trained to look at the numbers and not humans in a

00:17:50.560 --> 00:17:59.400
[Guest]: way or the human cost of it. So, bahut sari yeh sari cheezon ke beech mein art akele kaise

00:17:59.400 --> 00:18:05.000
[Guest]: survive karege, wo pata nahi. But art has survived for like through all these things.

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:11.080
[Guest]: And there's one thing I say this that the worst time to do comedy is actually the best

00:18:11.080 --> 00:18:16.040
[Guest]: time to do comedy, which is true for every art. So, worst time for any art is the best

00:18:16.040 --> 00:18:32.440
[Guest]: time for that art because jo cheez aapko, art ko, artist ko, sorry, I'll go thoda peeche.

00:18:32.440 --> 00:18:41.240
[Guest]: Toh ek baar kisi ne mujhse sawal poocha tha, kyunki usse kisi ne poocha tha, ki kavita logon

00:18:41.240 --> 00:18:47.320
[Guest]: ko kyun chahiye? Poetry kyun chahiye? What is the need of this, you know, need of poetry

00:18:47.320 --> 00:18:54.200
[Guest]: in this world? Is duniya mein poetry kisne maangi hai? Okay, people may ask for, let's

00:18:54.200 --> 00:19:02.160
[Guest]: say, cinema, which is something more tangible, you can see. Poetry kisko chahiye aur kyun

00:19:02.160 --> 00:19:10.480
[Guest]: chahiye? Aur uska jawab mujhe bahut time tak nahi mila tha, phir mujhe ek kavita mi thi.

00:19:10.480 --> 00:19:16.640
[Guest]: Mere paas matlab koi aisa convincing jawab nahi tha, kisi ek, jisne poocha hai, agar wo,

00:19:16.640 --> 00:19:23.320
[Guest]: shayad kisi, more chances, kisi engineering graduate ne poocha tha, jo kisi software company

00:19:23.320 --> 00:19:26.000
[Guest]: mein kaam kar raha tha. Aap bhi engineering graduate the, software

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:30.920
[Guest]: company mein kaam kiye the. Haan, isliye mujhe pata hai ki wahan aise

00:19:30.920 --> 00:19:37.080
[Guest]: sawal aa sakte hain wahan bhi. Kyunki main aise bahut saare logon se mila hun aur abhi

00:19:37.080 --> 00:19:44.480
[Guest]: tak milta rehta hun ki, asking ki, aur general ek jo atmosphere bhi pitle kuch saalon se

00:19:44.480 --> 00:19:53.200
[Guest]: banaya gaya hai against liberal arts or generally any kind of slightly intellectual activity.

00:19:53.200 --> 00:19:58.840
[Guest]: Wo ek anti-intellectualism ka jo daur hai, jo poori duniya mein chal raha hai. Humare

00:19:58.840 --> 00:20:07.520
[Guest]: yaha uska ek thoda alag, I think, kya boleng, variant hai, variant acha sabd hai aaj kare

00:20:07.520 --> 00:20:15.040
[Guest]: in cheezon ke liye. So, but haan, to poetry kise chahiye aur kyun chahiye? Iska jawab

00:20:15.040 --> 00:20:21.080
[Guest]: mujhe bahut tangentially hi mila, wo main abhi bhi samjha shayad nahi sakta hun us aadmi

00:20:21.080 --> 00:20:27.120
[Guest]: ko, jisne sawal poocha tha. But the thing is people have these very strong

00:20:27.120 --> 00:20:35.360
[Guest]: distinctions ki yeh poetry hai, yeh art hai, yeh science hai, yeh technology hai, yeh business

00:20:35.360 --> 00:20:43.700
[Guest]: hai, yeh linguistics hai, while living in a world which is flowing very smoothly from

00:20:43.700 --> 00:20:48.080
[Guest]: one thing to another. They are constantly, we are constantly moving and constantly doing

00:20:48.080 --> 00:20:54.080
[Guest]: things. Agar humne ghar mein apne phone charge pe lagaya hua hai, charger se nikala aur humne

00:20:54.080 --> 00:21:00.200
[Guest]: jaake TV on kiya, ya chai banayi, ya kuch bhi kiya. We are flowing between multiple

00:21:00.200 --> 00:21:09.200
[Guest]: things, a lot of which are actually result of, I would say, poetry because someone, somewhere

00:21:09.200 --> 00:21:20.560
[Guest]: got the sense of rhythm from learning or listening to music or poetry and that rhythm is what

00:21:20.560 --> 00:21:30.080
[Guest]: our life is or what makes our life easier to live or a joy to live a lot of times.

00:21:30.080 --> 00:21:36.560
[Guest]: Toh design jo hai, mujhe yeh samjh aaya, ultimately design is the core aur samjh, matlab aisa nahi

00:21:36.560 --> 00:21:41.120
[Guest]: ki mujhe jo samjh aaya hai, wo sach hai poora, but haan mujhe aisa lagta hai ki design is

00:21:41.120 --> 00:21:49.000
[Guest]: the core of everything, right from poetry to our daily utilities, to cinema, to music

00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:56.080
[Guest]: to and when I say design, it means three, four things. One, the aesthetic of it, which

00:21:56.080 --> 00:22:05.080
[Guest]: is very, very generally a bit of an abstract thing, but aesthetics humara dimaag samjh

00:22:05.080 --> 00:22:09.920
[Guest]: jaata hai, bhale hi hum zabaan se nahi bol paye, ki okay, kuch cheezein humko pasand

00:22:09.920 --> 00:22:13.360
[Guest]: aati hain, kuch cheezein nahi pasand aati hain aur koi humare paas uska jawab nahi

00:22:13.360 --> 00:22:19.840
[Guest]: hota hai, toh generally ek aesthetic feel hota hai uska. Doosra hai, sense of balance,

00:22:19.840 --> 00:22:26.520
[Guest]: symmetry aur asymmetry, which is again a choice, sometimes we choose asymmetry, sometimes we

00:22:26.520 --> 00:22:36.480
[Guest]: choose symmetry, toh symmetry, aesthetic and flow, generally film industry mein ek tare

00:22:36.480 --> 00:22:41.200
[Guest]: ka joke hai and people hate people who say this, ki koi bhi cheezein aap script padhe

00:22:41.200 --> 00:22:48.160
[Guest]: hain aur phir kisi ko padhne ko deyen aur bole ki maza nahi aaya, kyu nahi aaya maza.

00:22:48.160 --> 00:22:53.320
[Guest]: Toh samjhana logon ke liye mushkil hota hai, lekin log kehte hain feel nahi aayi. Toh feel

00:22:53.320 --> 00:22:59.560
[Guest]: nahi aayi jo hai, ultimately uske peeche, I think a lot of times it is the symmetry

00:22:59.560 --> 00:23:09.480
[Guest]: of things. They don't get the exact, it's a very, it's almost like making an alchemic

00:23:09.480 --> 00:23:18.000
[Guest]: portion where every element has to be in a very microgram kind of way correctly. Woh

00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:25.320
[Guest]: poetry mein, again you can see that balance. So, is tare ki bahut hi, again I know all

00:23:25.320 --> 00:23:30.920
[Guest]: of it is very, very abstract and I generally, you know, mushkil sawalon ke jawaab humesha

00:23:30.920 --> 00:23:38.040
[Guest]: mere paas abstract mein hote hain. Lekin poetry isliye chahiye, kyuki agar aapko chai bhi

00:23:38.040 --> 00:23:41.920
[Guest]: peeni hai toh aapko poetry chahiye, agar aapko phone charge karna hai poetry chahiye, aapko

00:23:41.920 --> 00:23:49.360
[Guest]: flight leni hai, aapko poetry chahiye, ya train leni hai, kuch bhi. All of it is put

00:23:49.360 --> 00:23:58.760
[Guest]: into this almost like a, so of course, poetry ekdum alag cheez hai, but poetry is the, you

00:23:58.760 --> 00:24:05.320
[Guest]: can say, ho sakta un sab cheezon se poetry nikli ho. That is also, I think, a good enough,

00:24:05.320 --> 00:24:11.080
[Guest]: good enough reason to love poetry, that it is a combination of all the good things in

00:24:11.080 --> 00:24:17.080
[Guest]: our lives around us. Aur poetry se woh cheeze nikli hain toh aur bhi achcha hai. So, either

00:24:17.080 --> 00:24:25.760
[Guest]: ways I think that was something which I kind of figured out slowly that the sense of whatever

00:24:25.760 --> 00:24:31.120
[Guest]: basic designs of things, jaise yeh table hai, iski yeh jo rounded edge hai, yeh sharp hoti

00:24:31.120 --> 00:24:35.360
[Guest]: toh abhi yahan pe haath rakhne mein dikkat hoti. Someone thought of it and whoever thought

00:24:35.360 --> 00:24:45.520
[Guest]: of it actually started with an abstract thought. It was not like ki, kyuki round shape is something

00:24:45.520 --> 00:24:56.840
[Guest]: which will, you know, I don't know, which will come to you in a very stream, stream

00:24:56.840 --> 00:25:04.960
[Guest]: of consciousness kind of a thing. Toh yeh saari cheezein waha se judhi hui lagti hai mujhe.

00:25:04.960 --> 00:25:12.960
[Guest]: Aur uske beech mein hum art aur usko distinct karne ke liye hum log baithe rehte hain, but

00:25:12.960 --> 00:25:15.960
[Guest]: trying to get back to where we started from, but I kind of.

00:25:15.960 --> 00:25:19.520
[Amit Varma]: I think you were talking about this friend of yours who asked yourself, why do we need

00:25:19.520 --> 00:25:22.880
[Guest]: poetry? Yeah, lekin uske pehle bhi I think, so I

00:25:22.880 --> 00:25:28.840
[Guest]: remember this story, like yahaan mein aaya tha, kyuki shayad we were talking about people

00:25:28.840 --> 00:25:36.440
[Guest]: trying to suppress art in a way and who are these people or what kind of people are these.

00:25:36.440 --> 00:25:48.040
[Guest]: And the thing is, so basically agar har cheez mein poetry aur har cheez mein art hai, toh

00:25:48.040 --> 00:25:55.880
[Guest]: log yeh samajh nahi paatein ki yeh sab ek hi hai, business bhi, they do try to do that

00:25:55.880 --> 00:26:02.320
[Guest]: thing, but ultimately I don't think they will succeed because art flourishes in these kind

00:26:02.320 --> 00:26:08.800
[Guest]: of situations, jahan pe aap dabhani ki koshish karein, jahan pe aap bolein ki ab toh jage

00:26:08.800 --> 00:26:15.840
[Guest]: hi nahi hai, tum nahi bol sakte ho. Ab tum nahi bol sakte ho is exactly the kind

00:26:15.840 --> 00:26:24.720
[Guest]: of space jahan se yeh table ki rounded edge aayi hogi, jahan se koi bhi naya thought aaya

00:26:24.720 --> 00:26:33.720
[Guest]: hoga pehli baar kisi ko. So that is, I think that's a good, of course, with all the privilege

00:26:33.720 --> 00:26:40.920
[Guest]: I have of saying that, okay, it's a good challenge to have people around you who don't want you

00:26:40.920 --> 00:26:47.480
[Guest]: to say stuff. Then you have to find ways to say that stuff or find stuff which they also

00:26:47.480 --> 00:26:53.600
[Guest]: don't know exists and can be talked about. Unke paas ek kitab hai ki yeh list hai us

00:26:53.600 --> 00:26:57.880
[Guest]: kitab mein ki yeh nahi bolna hai, iske baare mein nahi bolna hai, is tarah se nahi bolna

00:26:57.880 --> 00:27:09.600
[Guest]: hai. So either you invent, sometimes you invent new phrasing, sometimes you invent new thoughts

00:27:09.600 --> 00:27:15.960
[Guest]: and sometimes you end up inventing new languages to talk about the stuff which they don't want

00:27:15.960 --> 00:27:25.520
[Guest]: to be talked about. So that I think is a good, whatever, good challenge for artists.

00:27:25.520 --> 00:27:29.280
[Amit Varma]: So many things to double click on. What you just said is, it's like a Chinese doll, there

00:27:29.280 --> 00:27:33.960
[Amit Varma]: are like different layers within it and I'm just going to one of those dolls and talk

00:27:33.960 --> 00:27:38.640
[Amit Varma]: about, so I'll just think aloud from where you left off and that actually makes a lot

00:27:38.640 --> 00:27:44.600
[Amit Varma]: of sense to me what you just said. And I'll go into this slightly controversial space

00:27:44.600 --> 00:27:49.960
[Amit Varma]: about art and craft where I know many people will disagree with me. But the way I see it

00:27:49.960 --> 00:27:55.840
[Amit Varma]: is that everything we do, in everything we do, we are responding in ways that we are

00:27:55.840 --> 00:28:00.740
[Amit Varma]: wired to by default, right? So if I like a particular piece of music, it is because,

00:28:00.740 --> 00:28:05.440
[Amit Varma]: you know, a particular combination of notes will set off reactions in particular neurons

00:28:05.440 --> 00:28:09.680
[Amit Varma]: of mind, which might release dopamine, which might release something else. I'll, you know,

00:28:09.680 --> 00:28:14.480
[Amit Varma]: feel that a piano is tuneful, but an electric drill is noisy, and we are wired to find that

00:28:14.480 --> 00:28:19.200
[Amit Varma]: one is noise and the other is music if it's played properly. And those are kind of wirings.

00:28:19.200 --> 00:28:24.420
[Amit Varma]: Now, the point is, most of the time, the different ways in which we are getting manipulated by

00:28:24.420 --> 00:28:30.800
[Amit Varma]: what is around us, we are not aware of it, and we can't control it. So it is an uncontrollable,

00:28:30.800 --> 00:28:35.160
[Amit Varma]: you know, an omniscient engineer, as it were, may be able to see where all the pieces fit.

00:28:35.160 --> 00:28:39.680
[Amit Varma]: But otherwise, you can't. For example, I read this interesting study recently that if you

00:28:39.680 --> 00:28:43.760
[Amit Varma]: are making a pitch to someone, you know, if they if they're drinking a warm drink, they're

00:28:43.760 --> 00:28:47.560
[Amit Varma]: more likely to say yes. And if they're drinking a cold drink, now, this could be one of those

00:28:47.560 --> 00:28:52.080
[Amit Varma]: behavioral psychology experiments, which you can't really replicate. But there are all

00:28:52.080 --> 00:28:57.840
[Amit Varma]: kinds of fascinating things going on under the surface. I get your point that, you know,

00:28:57.840 --> 00:29:02.960
[Amit Varma]: there are things which have a direct impact on us, which we can measure and understand

00:29:02.960 --> 00:29:08.480
[Amit Varma]: that I am feeling this way because of this. And there are other things where we don't

00:29:08.480 --> 00:29:12.600
[Amit Varma]: know why we are feeling in a particular way. A poem could make me want to cry, but I may

00:29:12.600 --> 00:29:22.040
[Amit Varma]: not be able to tell you exactly why. I just know that I feel that way. If I had enough

00:29:22.040 --> 00:29:27.040
[Amit Varma]: knowledge, I could tell you the science behind it. But obviously, we don't. So it seems art

00:29:27.040 --> 00:29:32.160
[Amit Varma]: and this is why I've kind of also come to believe and this is a sideways point that

00:29:32.160 --> 00:29:37.880
[Amit Varma]: actually craft and art are the same thing. But when there is craft where we cannot understand

00:29:37.880 --> 00:29:43.080
[Amit Varma]: the mechanics, like why a poem makes me cry, we call it art, but it's actually craft happening

00:29:43.080 --> 00:29:47.320
[Amit Varma]: subconsciously. Because I get a lot of pushback when I say this.

00:29:47.320 --> 00:29:55.040
[Guest]: That craft and art are same thing? Yeah. Really? Okay. I don't know. No, I think I don't understand

00:29:55.040 --> 00:30:01.880
[Guest]: why the pushback because yeah, maybe people think that art is slightly more refined form

00:30:01.880 --> 00:30:07.880
[Guest]: of craft or something or artists are more valuable than craftsperson. Maybe that's what

00:30:07.880 --> 00:30:16.720
[Guest]: they think. But no, but I completely agree on that. Craft and art are actually the same

00:30:16.720 --> 00:30:24.600
[Guest]: thing. There are some things that we understand how they are happening. For example, like

00:30:24.600 --> 00:30:30.480
[Guest]: look at some of the some of the sculptures, some of the folk arts people do and some of

00:30:30.480 --> 00:30:33.880
[Guest]: the paintings and they'll, you know,

00:30:33.880 --> 00:30:42.200
[Guest]: there will be some things that you won't be able to do even after 50 years of training.

00:30:42.200 --> 00:30:52.640
[Guest]: So, by giving it the status of craft, which is given a little lower status, I don't, I

00:30:52.640 --> 00:31:02.000
[Guest]: believe that's, that's just elitism for lack of a better word. But ultimately, yes, both

00:31:02.000 --> 00:31:10.840
[Guest]: are processes. Some processes we understand and some processes we deliberately, yeah,

00:31:10.840 --> 00:31:15.800
[Guest]: probably don't want people to understand and to call ourselves artists.

00:31:15.800 --> 00:31:25.800
[Guest]: I've seen a lot of writers do that. And the writers benefit from that because you generally

00:31:25.800 --> 00:31:35.760
[Guest]: have to deal with very oppressive producers. So, you have to keep that slight mystery of

00:31:35.760 --> 00:31:46.000
[Guest]: ki main bahut soch ke maine yeh likha hai. Kai baar hota hai ki wo auto mein likha hota

00:31:46.000 --> 00:31:48.560
[Guest]: hai apne jaate hue. Lekin if you actually reveal the value of it. So, sometimes actually

00:31:48.560 --> 00:32:01.120
[Guest]: there is a just thinking like on the go. But there is actually a chance that a lot of art,

00:32:01.120 --> 00:32:08.800
[Guest]: in fact, it's not a chance. I think a lot of art is fraud, but very little of craft

00:32:08.800 --> 00:32:16.320
[Guest]: can be fraud. It is seen, it is right there. You can't cheat on that. Agar aapne wo achcha

00:32:16.320 --> 00:32:21.480
[Guest]: kaam kiya hai, wo dikh raha hai, wo uske liye enough there are. So, craft is probably a

00:32:21.480 --> 00:32:28.900
[Guest]: more peer-reviewed way of judging things. Like, okay, it is peer-reviewed, it is craft.

00:32:28.900 --> 00:32:39.080
[Guest]: Something which doesn't require any peer-review is art. So, maybe we can say homeopathy is

00:32:39.080 --> 00:32:50.760
[Guest]: art and allopathy is craft. My point is art can sometimes be homeopathy also.

00:32:50.760 --> 00:32:56.440
[Amit Varma]: It can be like an example of fraud art basically. So, another of the Chinese boxes I wanted

00:32:56.440 --> 00:33:02.760
[Amit Varma]: to touch down upon actually has something to do with, you know, one of the ways in which

00:33:02.760 --> 00:33:10.960
[Amit Varma]: I have kind of, one, changed my mind during the course of this podcast. And two, also

00:33:10.960 --> 00:33:15.120
[Amit Varma]: a realization I've had about something I was mistaken about all my life. Now, the thing

00:33:15.120 --> 00:33:21.520
[Amit Varma]: is growing up in a sort of, you know, elite English-speaking bubble in big cities all

00:33:21.520 --> 00:33:29.520
[Amit Varma]: my life, my conception of my country was that it's basically, you know, it's a liberal space,

00:33:29.520 --> 00:33:34.840
[Amit Varma]: we're tolerant, we're secular, all of that. That was kind of my conception. Now, you know,

00:33:34.840 --> 00:33:38.400
[Amit Varma]: as you kind of grow older, the different layers slip off your eyes. You see gender, you see

00:33:38.400 --> 00:33:44.520
[Amit Varma]: caste, you see religion, you see all of those various areas in which, but that's not exactly

00:33:44.520 --> 00:33:50.720
[Amit Varma]: true. And I remember I did an episode with JP Narayan once, episode 150, where I, you

00:33:50.720 --> 00:33:55.360
[Amit Varma]: know, posed the notion to him that India is a deeply liberal society. And his point was

00:33:55.360 --> 00:33:59.680
[Amit Varma]: no, but if you look at the opposite is also true, you know, that old cliche about India.

00:33:59.680 --> 00:34:05.200
[Amit Varma]: And if you actually look at how assimilative we are in terms of food and clothes and all

00:34:05.200 --> 00:34:11.440
[Amit Varma]: of that, you could also make the opposite case. Now, what I kind of my beginning premise

00:34:11.440 --> 00:34:16.680
[Amit Varma]: still a few years ago always was that we are essentially we are liberal, we get along fine,

00:34:16.680 --> 00:34:20.800
[Amit Varma]: we are a big melting pot, which is great, which is what I love about this country. And

00:34:20.800 --> 00:34:25.520
[Amit Varma]: there are fringes and there are, you know, there are these moments on the fringe. What

00:34:25.520 --> 00:34:29.400
[Amit Varma]: I have come to realize through talking with various guests like Akshay Mukul and many

00:34:29.400 --> 00:34:34.040
[Amit Varma]: others on the show, is that that is not the case that this was our society was always

00:34:34.040 --> 00:34:39.600
[Amit Varma]: deeply liberal. I have been in a small bubble, you know, in a sense, we are the fringe. And

00:34:39.600 --> 00:34:45.040
[Amit Varma]: we never kind of saw this earlier. In fact, the larger point about the constitution that

00:34:45.040 --> 00:34:50.640
[Amit Varma]: comes up here is that our constitution was a liberal constitution, not as liberal as

00:34:50.640 --> 00:34:55.320
[Amit Varma]: I would like, but still more liberal than society was a liberal constitution imposed

00:34:55.320 --> 00:35:01.440
[Amit Varma]: on an illiberal society. And as any former engineer would know, ki aap top down se you

00:35:01.440 --> 00:35:05.800
[Amit Varma]: can't engineer society, you know, in that sense, Gandhi was right that our challenge

00:35:05.800 --> 00:35:10.560
[Amit Varma]: is to change society from within. We could not do that. We put a constitution there,

00:35:10.560 --> 00:35:15.240
[Amit Varma]: we put random laws there, and we assume ki society badal jayega. And today politics has

00:35:15.240 --> 00:35:21.000
[Amit Varma]: caught up with society. And I thought of this because that point you made earlier about

00:35:21.000 --> 00:35:25.360
[Amit Varma]: ki media mein aaj jo log hai na, it's not that they've been asked to bend in their crawling,

00:35:25.360 --> 00:35:31.440
[Amit Varma]: wo waise hi hai. They are fundamentally, you know, bigoted and anti Muslim and all of that.

00:35:31.440 --> 00:35:34.720
[Amit Varma]: So they are going along with the program, you don't need to suppress democracy for this,

00:35:34.720 --> 00:35:39.920
[Amit Varma]: you have true believers, this is the expression of our democracy. Now, my question to you

00:35:39.920 --> 00:35:45.280
[Amit Varma]: as someone who is not so much from the same bubble as me, who's lived in small town India,

00:35:45.280 --> 00:35:51.120
[Amit Varma]: who's, you know, spoken a different language and so on is, is this broadly true that we

00:35:51.120 --> 00:35:57.320
[Amit Varma]: were always this illiberal and the politics is really supply responding to demand. And

00:35:57.320 --> 00:36:01.480
[Amit Varma]: all of this was pent up inside people couldn't express it. But now they are emboldened to

00:36:01.480 --> 00:36:07.000
[Amit Varma]: express their bigotry because they see everybody else around them openly expressing it. Or

00:36:07.000 --> 00:36:12.280
[Amit Varma]: have we actually become sort of worse? And I know, you know, it becomes a vicious circle

00:36:12.280 --> 00:36:17.160
[Amit Varma]: at some point in time. But what is your sense of that, like my deeply pessimistic sense

00:36:17.160 --> 00:36:21.560
[Amit Varma]: is that, hey, we were always like this at some point or the other, this was inevitable.

00:36:21.560 --> 00:36:25.120
[Amit Varma]: And the liberal project as it were, however, you define liberal, the liberal project as

00:36:25.120 --> 00:36:28.480
[Amit Varma]: it were, failed a long, long time ago.

00:36:28.480 --> 00:36:44.480
[Guest]: So, yeah, I think we were always illiberal. I grew up in UP in the 80s and 80s and 90s.

00:36:44.480 --> 00:36:59.480
[Guest]: It has always been so difficult for minorities, for Muslims, for Dalits in this country. It

00:36:59.480 --> 00:37:19.480
[Guest]: was a bit of a give and take kind of a process, where somebody tried to take incentives, but

00:37:19.480 --> 00:37:30.480
[Guest]: he got it, so others thought, yes, you get it. Then the one who was giving it, he thought,

00:37:30.480 --> 00:37:37.480
[Guest]: yes, yes, you have to give it, so he started giving it. So, it was a process like that.

00:37:37.480 --> 00:37:44.680
[Guest]: I don't think there was any clear plan. And that is one of our blessings that the people

00:37:44.680 --> 00:37:51.280
[Guest]: in power rarely have a clear plan, and so we can find our way till they are picking up

00:37:51.280 --> 00:37:59.280
[Guest]: the gun. We can reach the door in that time. So, things like that. But I think our country

00:37:59.280 --> 00:38:07.280
[Guest]: has always been illiberal. And still, why did it not look so openly? There can be many

00:38:07.280 --> 00:38:20.680
[Guest]: reasons. There was a certain incentive, just like now there is an incentive. There was

00:38:20.680 --> 00:38:29.880
[Guest]: a certain incentive in showing yourself as a Gandhian, as a Nehruvian, and both of these,

00:38:29.880 --> 00:38:34.880
[Guest]: when I say Gandhian and Nehruvian, both of these kind of represented in people's heads

00:38:34.880 --> 00:38:42.880
[Guest]: the idea of a secular and, you know, all-encompassing nationalism, which kind of doesn't look at

00:38:42.880 --> 00:38:48.880
[Guest]: caste or creed or, you know, gender was always, I think gender was never even discussed.

00:38:48.880 --> 00:38:54.880
[Guest]: It has always been an illiberal aspect that no one is surprised, and it has always been

00:38:54.880 --> 00:39:04.880
[Guest]: accepted that it is like that, and we will be like that. Gradually, when the Western

00:39:04.880 --> 00:39:10.880
[Guest]: influence will come, we will gradually deteriorate or improve from whichever angle you want to

00:39:10.880 --> 00:39:14.880
[Guest]: see this thing. But it has always been there, and why is it now being expressed more openly

00:39:14.880 --> 00:39:19.880
[Guest]: from the front? Because now there is an incentive, and earlier there was an incentive for something

00:39:19.880 --> 00:39:25.880
[Guest]: which was again not your true self, but that was something which you were putting up an

00:39:25.880 --> 00:39:36.880
[Guest]: act, that yes, we go and accept every person as our own, and those kinds of things which

00:39:36.880 --> 00:39:46.880
[Guest]: used to happen at that time, because of which a lot of people who were privileged enough

00:39:46.880 --> 00:39:56.880
[Guest]: to live in a bubble from, and not just from the Hindu religion, but from, you know, Muslims

00:39:56.880 --> 00:40:09.880
[Guest]: also, they were kind of spared the discrimination, and then they started believing in that to

00:40:09.880 --> 00:40:16.880
[Guest]: be the only India that exists, a very, you know, accepting and very secular kind of an

00:40:16.880 --> 00:40:25.880
[Guest]: image. But now it has happened that, as we are seeing in front of us, now the fire has

00:40:25.880 --> 00:40:36.880
[Guest]: increased so much that now everyone is feeling its flame. So, the most privileged people

00:40:36.880 --> 00:40:44.880
[Guest]: like us, who have always, you know, lived, and we are still, I mean, in many ways we

00:40:44.880 --> 00:40:50.880
[Guest]: are not facing the heat of that oppression. But now at least we can see it, we can see

00:40:50.880 --> 00:40:57.880
[Guest]: it happening to people around us, people like us, and now we are like, oh, this India has

00:40:57.880 --> 00:41:03.880
[Guest]: suddenly become very bad. But India was like that, earlier it was for those people whom

00:41:03.880 --> 00:41:10.880
[Guest]: we did not see, or whom we could not see, or could not be seen. Now you do not have

00:41:10.880 --> 00:41:17.880
[Guest]: to look there. Now you can imagine that this is happening to us, so then, those who do

00:41:17.880 --> 00:41:24.880
[Guest]: not have any power, and in today's times, power equals also social media presence.

00:41:24.880 --> 00:41:34.880
[Guest]: So, if they are not there, then what kind of India they are seeing for the last 70-75

00:41:34.880 --> 00:41:39.880
[Guest]: years, we can understand a little bit, I think.

00:41:39.880 --> 00:41:43.880
[Amit Varma]: Just to give context to the listeners, what fire you are talking about, just now we were

00:41:43.880 --> 00:41:47.880
[Amit Varma]: interrupted by this massive fire, we can see from my window here, which was in Chitrakoot

00:41:47.880 --> 00:41:52.880
[Amit Varma]: studio. So, we actually took a little bit of a break, and Varun made a couple of calls

00:41:52.880 --> 00:41:57.880
[Amit Varma]: and figured out that, okay, it happened on film set, but the information we have so far

00:41:57.880 --> 00:42:05.880
[Amit Varma]: is that everyone is safe, and the smoke from that was like dwarfing the entire city, but

00:42:05.880 --> 00:42:10.880
[Amit Varma]: you could look out of some other window and not see that smoke. And what you spoke about

00:42:10.880 --> 00:42:14.880
[Amit Varma]: incentives is interesting, there was a Turkish sociologist called Timur Kuran, there is,

00:42:14.880 --> 00:42:19.880
[Amit Varma]: he is still alive, who in 1999 wrote a book called Private Truths, Public Lies, and he

00:42:19.880 --> 00:42:24.880
[Amit Varma]: came up in that with the term preference falsification. And preference falsification is you don't

00:42:24.880 --> 00:42:28.880
[Amit Varma]: reveal what you are really feeling. So, the example he gave was that in Soviet Union,

00:42:28.880 --> 00:42:33.880
[Amit Varma]: everybody hated the authorities, but nobody had the guts to say it, because everyone has

00:42:33.880 --> 00:42:38.880
[Amit Varma]: the incentive to complain and you don't want to get into trouble. So, if you have a problem

00:42:38.880 --> 00:42:42.880
[Amit Varma]: with the regime, you believe you are the only one to have a problem with the regime because

00:42:42.880 --> 00:42:46.880
[Amit Varma]: you don't hear anyone else say it. So, your silence is preference falsification. And the

00:42:46.880 --> 00:42:51.880
[Amit Varma]: term Kuran used for what happened when the Soviet Union fell apart was that there was

00:42:51.880 --> 00:42:55.880
[Amit Varma]: a preference cascade, that you hear a few people expressing themselves, you realize

00:42:55.880 --> 00:43:01.880
[Amit Varma]: you're not alone, and you go with it. And my sense is that social media did the same

00:43:01.880 --> 00:43:06.880
[Amit Varma]: thing in India, that many of us were closet bigots. In private, you may hate Muslims,

00:43:06.880 --> 00:43:10.880
[Amit Varma]: or you may think a woman's place is in the kitchen, or, you know, the person who works

00:43:10.880 --> 00:43:15.880
[Amit Varma]: at your house, you leave him a different glass. But publicly, you may not express these things,

00:43:15.880 --> 00:43:20.880
[Unknown]: you may project yourself as progressive or what you call Gandhian or whatever. But then

00:43:20.880 --> 00:43:25.880
[Amit Varma]: social media tips the balance over, where suddenly you realize I'm not the only one,

00:43:25.880 --> 00:43:29.880
[Amit Varma]: other people feel like me. And then you realize bloody hell, the majority feels like me. And

00:43:29.880 --> 00:43:35.880
[Amit Varma]: that empowers you to kind of, you know, go for it. And what that also, I think, drives

00:43:35.880 --> 00:43:41.880
[Amit Varma]: home is that, you know, one thing that I do believe is that we contain multitudes, that

00:43:41.880 --> 00:43:47.880
[Amit Varma]: a bigot is not only a bigot, that nobody is kind of black and white. And the great failure,

00:43:47.880 --> 00:43:52.880
[Amit Varma]: therefore, especially the great failure of our politics, as I see it today, is a narrative

00:43:52.880 --> 00:43:58.880
[Amit Varma]: failure that we are not recognizing, you know, that somebody may have these unpleasant aspects

00:43:58.880 --> 00:44:03.880
[Amit Varma]: to her character, but she may also want better schools for her children or whatever. And

00:44:03.880 --> 00:44:08.880
[Amit Varma]: we are not building those narratives and appealing to them. And, you know, as a political philosopher

00:44:08.880 --> 00:44:14.880
[Amit Varma]: Carl Schmitt said that the essential quality you need to be successful in politics is you

00:44:14.880 --> 00:44:19.880
[Amit Varma]: have to other somebody, right? It is always anger, you know, hope will not get you words.

00:44:19.880 --> 00:44:24.880
[Amit Varma]: And I see that happening. And my question to you, therefore, as an artist is this, that

00:44:24.880 --> 00:44:33.880
[Amit Varma]: at one level as an artist, you want to embrace the individuals, the complexity of individuals

00:44:33.880 --> 00:44:38.880
[Amit Varma]: and their particular circumstances and pay respect to that. So no character becomes a

00:44:38.880 --> 00:44:43.880
[Amit Varma]: cliche, that no character, you don't essentialize a character ki yeh Muslim hai, yeh Dalit hai

00:44:43.880 --> 00:44:48.880
[Amit Varma]: or whatever. They are complex characters, the characters you see in Masana, complex

00:44:48.880 --> 00:44:53.880
[Amit Varma]: characters, you're dealing and engaging with that complexity. At the same time, there is

00:44:53.880 --> 00:45:00.880
[Amit Varma]: also that urge to sort of reflect what is happening in the world around you. And Kundera,

00:45:00.880 --> 00:45:05.880
[Amit Varma]: Milan Kundera once, you know, wrote an essay about how art and politics, there is this

00:45:05.880 --> 00:45:09.880
[Amit Varma]: tension between them that they cannot mix. If you have too much politics in art, then

00:45:09.880 --> 00:45:14.880
[Amit Varma]: it becomes propaganda. I mean, my words from what I remember, I don't know the exact words

00:45:14.880 --> 00:45:19.880
[Amit Varma]: he wrote. So how does one strike this balance? Because at one level, I imagine that someone

00:45:19.880 --> 00:45:24.880
[Amit Varma]: like you would be creating different arts 50 years ago or 200 years ago or whatever,

00:45:24.880 --> 00:45:28.880
[Amit Varma]: because obviously your circumstances, the background, everything is different. So you

00:45:28.880 --> 00:45:33.880
[Amit Varma]: might be telling the same kind of stories of individuals, but in a different backdrop.

00:45:33.880 --> 00:45:39.880
[Amit Varma]: But how much does the backdrop affect it? And what is that balance that you then have

00:45:39.880 --> 00:45:40.880
[Amit Varma]: to work?

00:45:40.880 --> 00:45:48.880
[Guest]: So, yeah, that's a very, I would say, good question. Good is not the right word. That's

00:45:48.880 --> 00:45:58.880
[Guest]: a very provocative question. Because I have thought about this a lot and a lot of questions

00:45:58.880 --> 00:46:05.880
[Guest]: have come up. I mean, a lot of people have probably thought about how much politics should

00:46:05.880 --> 00:46:13.880
[Guest]: come in art and how it should come. So, I believe that in today's date, especially,

00:46:13.880 --> 00:46:21.880
[Guest]: the answers to this question might be different in every era or every decade. In this decade,

00:46:21.880 --> 00:46:33.880
[Guest]: I feel that art should exist in itself with its truth. That is a big revolution in itself

00:46:33.880 --> 00:46:40.880
[Guest]: right now. If you manage to say what you want to say, and even if it's a story which is

00:46:40.880 --> 00:46:46.880
[Guest]: non-political, you know, in its, whatever, in its essence or first look, you feel that

00:46:46.880 --> 00:46:52.880
[Guest]: it's completely non-political. That too should come with its full truth. That has always

00:46:52.880 --> 00:47:00.880
[Guest]: been a challenge. But in today's time, that challenge is even bigger. Because, as I believe,

00:47:00.880 --> 00:47:13.880
[Guest]: you know, the major fight is not between right wing and liberals or right wing and left wing

00:47:13.880 --> 00:47:21.880
[Guest]: or, you know, or orthodoxy versus modernism. No, the fight right now is simply between

00:47:21.880 --> 00:47:29.880
[Guest]: scientific temperament and lack of scientific temperament. And when you say scientific temperament,

00:47:29.880 --> 00:47:42.880
[Guest]: in a story or in art, what that means, that simply means dedication to truth. What is

00:47:42.880 --> 00:47:49.880
[Guest]: science in a very, you know, even etymologically, it's just a quest for truth and finding truth.

00:47:49.880 --> 00:47:56.880
[Guest]: So, how will that truth come in art? That truth comes from authenticity. So, for me,

00:47:56.880 --> 00:48:03.880
[Guest]: authenticity is its own aesthetic and the biggest aesthetic. Everything else is fine,

00:48:03.880 --> 00:48:11.880
[Guest]: we think of 50 things, color palette or light or generally where to shoot and how, or any

00:48:11.880 --> 00:48:18.880
[Guest]: art, I'm saying, any visual art I'm talking about. In visual art, authenticity is the

00:48:18.880 --> 00:48:27.880
[Guest]: biggest aesthetic and to bring that authenticity, you have to fight against all kinds of non

00:48:27.880 --> 00:48:34.880
[Guest]: or anti-science temperament at every stage. Right from when you are writing with your

00:48:34.880 --> 00:48:40.880
[Guest]: own anti-scientific temperament part of your brain, which keeps telling you to not write

00:48:40.880 --> 00:48:45.880
[Guest]: this or not, or you'll be, you know, no one will like this or no one will really approve

00:48:45.880 --> 00:48:51.880
[Guest]: this because this is too, whatever, this is offensive to someone. Then when you start

00:48:51.880 --> 00:48:58.880
[Guest]: pitching, so for bringing that art from that idea to the final marketplace, there are,

00:48:58.880 --> 00:49:05.880
[Guest]: you have to deal with 10 different, at least 10 different bosses who have their own idea

00:49:05.880 --> 00:49:11.880
[Guest]: of what art should be or what art should not be in today's times. So, this whole struggle

00:49:11.880 --> 00:49:21.880
[Guest]: is ultimately of temperament, scientific temperament. Now, in between that, your question

00:49:21.880 --> 00:49:31.880
[Guest]: fits in such a way that how much politics should come in art in today's time. People

00:49:31.880 --> 00:49:42.880
[Guest]: have become very over, there were two terms during COVID, I forgot. One is specificity

00:49:42.880 --> 00:49:48.880
[Guest]: and one is, the tests that used to be there, which are still going on, of course. So, one

00:49:48.880 --> 00:49:55.880
[Guest]: is super specific, the antigen test and one is super, I mean there is one test which

00:49:55.880 --> 00:50:02.880
[Guest]: will tell you, even if there is a small molecule in it, whether it is COVID or not. And there

00:50:02.880 --> 00:50:09.880
[Guest]: is one test which will tell you how much it is. It won't tell you whether you have it

00:50:09.880 --> 00:50:15.880
[Guest]: or not, but it tells you how much it is. So, right now, people have become super specific

00:50:15.880 --> 00:50:22.880
[Guest]: about political affiliations. They, even to the extent, and it is being, whatever, it

00:50:22.880 --> 00:50:26.880
[Guest]: is being, it is a project. It's not like it has happened by itself in people, but it

00:50:26.880 --> 00:50:30.880
[Guest]: is a project where people now think that whoever we are buying vegetables from is a Hindu or

00:50:30.880 --> 00:50:35.880
[Guest]: a Muslim, or whoever we are buying groceries from, or whoever we are listening to, which

00:50:35.880 --> 00:50:44.880
[Guest]: side of the political spectrum they are on. At that time, if someone sees your politics

00:50:44.880 --> 00:50:52.880
[Guest]: in the beginning itself, you are losing, no matter what side of, even if you are, you

00:50:52.880 --> 00:50:58.880
[Guest]: know, even if you are making an agenda, propaganda piece and, you know, the government has given

00:50:58.880 --> 00:51:05.880
[Guest]: you money to do their work. Even then, if it is seen in your work, then it is as an

00:51:05.880 --> 00:51:11.880
[Guest]: artist you lose. As a businessman, maybe you will win and you will win a lot, but as an

00:51:11.880 --> 00:51:20.880
[Guest]: artist, if that is truly your quest in life, you are losing. So, art, co-politics, art

00:51:20.880 --> 00:51:24.880
[Guest]: mein politics, aaj ki tarikh mein bilkul nahi dikh sakta. There was a time when, probably

00:51:24.880 --> 00:51:34.880
[Guest]: in the 50s and 60s, that was supposed to be a, you know, a value addition to your art.

00:51:34.880 --> 00:51:39.880
[Guest]: If you were vocal about your politics through the art, right, from, you know, the poster

00:51:39.880 --> 00:51:45.880
[Guest]: to the text, to the subtext, to the choice of actors, to the choice of music or whatever,

00:51:45.880 --> 00:51:52.880
[Guest]: everything. Aaj mujhe lagta hai ki agar, kyuki yeh hi ek hissa bacha hai, aaj hi iklauti

00:51:52.880 --> 00:52:00.880
[Guest]: cheez bachi hai, which can engage you even if you are on the other side of the spectrum,

00:52:00.880 --> 00:52:07.880
[Guest]: in terms of political ideology. Aap op-ed, why the op-eds are dead, according to me,

00:52:07.880 --> 00:52:16.880
[Guest]: or why the newspaper is dead itself, because it is now completely, whatever, marked by

00:52:16.880 --> 00:52:22.880
[Guest]: people, ki yeh wo hai. Acha, scroll hum padhenge hi nahi. Scroll mein meri bhi tarikh likhi

00:52:22.880 --> 00:52:27.880
[Guest]: hai. Mein nahi padhunga, kyuki main manta hi nahi, wo jo bhi likhte hai, wo sach hai.

00:52:27.880 --> 00:52:33.880
[Guest]: Main manta hi nahi, wo kuch bhi ho. Agar wo simple scroll nahi yeh chhaap diya ki paani

00:52:33.880 --> 00:52:37.880
[Guest]: ka chemical formula H2O hota hai, main nahi manunga, kyuki yeh scroll nahi likha hai,

00:52:37.880 --> 00:52:45.880
[Guest]: wahan tak chali gayi yeh baat. Toh uss time mein, art iklauti cheez hai. Art mein, when

00:52:45.880 --> 00:52:53.880
[Guest]: I say art, I mean storytelling, a narrative art form. It could be storytelling, it could

00:52:53.880 --> 00:53:04.880
[Guest]: be comedy, it could be music of some sort. Jahan pe, on the face of it, people can't

00:53:04.880 --> 00:53:09.880
[Guest]: really say ki yeh iss side hai, aur uss side hai. Thik hai, aapne, wahan tak baat ponch

00:53:09.880 --> 00:53:13.880
[Guest]: gayi hai ki aapne logon ko bhi identify karna shuru kar diya hai, ki yeh aadmi hi aisa hai,

00:53:13.880 --> 00:53:18.880
[Guest]: iski bhale hi yeh kuch bhi bol raha ho, main nahi sununga hai, bhale hi meri tarikh kar

00:53:18.880 --> 00:53:31.880
[Guest]: hai. Lekin, uss time mein, it becomes even more important for an artist to tell stories

00:53:31.880 --> 00:53:38.880
[Guest]: in a neutral way. Not be neutral, uss pe main second part pe aata hoon ki phir apni politics

00:53:38.880 --> 00:53:42.880
[Guest]: ka hum kya karein, hum kahan leke jayein apni politics, agar hum apne art mein bhi nahi

00:53:42.880 --> 00:53:51.880
[Guest]: bol sakte hain. But it is not just, not just a virtue of the artist right now to be neutral,

00:53:51.880 --> 00:54:02.880
[Guest]: it is the necessity for an artist in these times to be neutral, to be treated without

00:54:02.880 --> 00:54:09.880
[Guest]: doubt by whoever you are creating the art for, and I am creating my art for everyone,

00:54:09.880 --> 00:54:17.880
[Guest]: and I don't really want, you know, to be bracketed or categorized into theek hai,

00:54:17.880 --> 00:54:21.880
[Guest]: art dekhne ke baad aap jo bhi dekhenge, uske baad aapke andar jo bhi aate hain sawal wo

00:54:21.880 --> 00:54:25.880
[Guest]: theek hai, uske saath aapko rehna hai, aur phir usmein aapko ho sakta hai gussa aaye

00:54:25.880 --> 00:54:31.880
[Guest]: ki isne yeh kaise dikha diya hai, yeh kyun bola. But engage karna zaruri hai, aur wo

00:54:31.880 --> 00:54:38.880
[Guest]: engagement ki power iss samein mere khyal se sirf art mein bachi hai, aur yahan tak ki

00:54:38.880 --> 00:54:43.880
[Guest]: news mein bhi nahi bachi hai. News bhi ab itni zyada news which is supposed to be simply

00:54:43.880 --> 00:54:52.880
[Guest]: stated facts is now seen as painted, you know, right wing, and this is again the world over.

00:54:52.880 --> 00:54:57.880
[Guest]: America mein there is a very clear distinction between what is Fox News and what is CNN,

00:54:57.880 --> 00:55:05.880
[Guest]: wo sab ke ek bracket hain, aur sabko pata hai, aur ussi tarah se wo, yahan bhi har cheez

00:55:05.880 --> 00:55:10.880
[Guest]: ki tarah se bat gayi, aur yahan pe batwara jo hai wo bahut hi skewed sa hai, America jitna

00:55:10.880 --> 00:55:15.880
[Guest]: balanced bhi nahi hai, ki theek hai aade log idhar hain, aade udhar hain, yahan to 80-90%

00:55:15.880 --> 00:55:18.880
[Guest]: log ek tarah ka media dekh rahe hain, aur ek tarah ki cheeze consume kar rahe hain, aur

00:55:18.880 --> 00:55:26.880
[Guest]: 10% hai jo apna koshish kar rahe hain ki unki baat koi sune. To uss time mein I feel aapko

00:55:26.880 --> 00:55:35.880
[Guest]: aapki story bhale hi kitni political ho, it has to first appeal to the viewer or listener

00:55:35.880 --> 00:55:43.880
[Guest]: as a story, as simply a human story of our times or of our people or something. Then

00:55:43.880 --> 00:55:51.880
[Guest]: doosra sawal aata hai ki phir hum politics ka kya karein apni. To politics aap rakhe

00:55:51.880 --> 00:55:57.880
[Guest]: hain, lekin usko agar aap top layer ya second layer ya third layer bhi apni kahaani mein

00:55:57.880 --> 00:56:08.880
[Guest]: banayenge, to I think that is a failure of imagination. You have to actually need it

00:56:08.880 --> 00:56:17.880
[Guest]: into your existence, into your personality, into your soul, into your craft, that it is

00:56:17.880 --> 00:56:22.880
[Guest]: there but it is not there. It is there in every character you create, it is there in

00:56:22.880 --> 00:56:33.880
[Guest]: every gesture you see on paper or on screen, but it's not ever distinguishable or kind

00:56:33.880 --> 00:56:41.880
[Guest]: of stands out as its own. To ab jaise aat, kisi roti khao to imagine karna mushkil hai

00:56:41.880 --> 00:56:48.880
[Guest]: na ki kahaan, jo mujhe meshaan bahut surprising lagta hai jab bhi mein chapati, roti khaata

00:56:48.880 --> 00:56:54.880
[Guest]: ho ki yeh jo khet hum dekh rahein hain, train se aate jaate hain, uspe jo gehun lagi hai,

00:56:54.880 --> 00:56:58.880
[Guest]: usse yeh cheez ban sakti hai aur kitni lambi journey rahi hai and we take it kind of for

00:56:58.880 --> 00:57:02.880
[Guest]: granted ki theek hai humare saamne roti hai but it's such a huge journey and something

00:57:02.880 --> 00:57:08.880
[Guest]: has taken so many forms and shapes and then it has been transported from some village

00:57:08.880 --> 00:57:13.880
[Guest]: in Madhya Pradesh to Bombay, then usko humne piswaaya hai, phir humne usme paani milaaya

00:57:13.880 --> 00:57:18.880
[Guest]: hai aur phir usko bahut achche se guntha hai, phir usko phula diya hai. There is so much

00:57:18.880 --> 00:57:24.880
[Guest]: science and there is so much economy and there is so much, I would say, society in just that

00:57:24.880 --> 00:57:36.880
[Guest]: ek chapati. Ab aap chapati mein dhoondein ki uska mitti kahaan hai ya wo paani kahaan

00:57:36.880 --> 00:57:41.880
[Guest]: hai ya wo pesticide kahaan hai. It's all there. It's all there. That's why you are able to

00:57:41.880 --> 00:57:50.880
[Guest]: eat that thing and feel nourished but it's not really visible there. It is there. So

00:57:50.880 --> 00:57:59.880
[Guest]: utna zyada you have to basically first get if you want, if you think you have a politics

00:57:59.880 --> 00:58:05.880
[Guest]: and everyone has their politics even if they don't know it and in fact my friend Sanjay

00:58:05.880 --> 00:58:11.880
[Guest]: says in our show Aise Taise Democracy ki if you don't choose your politics, your politics

00:58:11.880 --> 00:58:17.880
[Guest]: will choose you at some point. So ultimately politics toh hai aapki. Toh agar hai toh then

00:58:17.880 --> 00:58:26.880
[Guest]: be aware of what it is and then be so aware that you put it in your work but not put it

00:58:26.880 --> 00:58:32.880
[Guest]: in your work, put it just in your whole personality that it automatically is there. If you try

00:58:32.880 --> 00:58:37.880
[Guest]: to write a story and then say achha iski politics kuch kar dete hain, ispe na ab ye kar dete

00:58:37.880 --> 00:58:42.880
[Guest]: hain ki iski politics aise kar dete hain ki liberal ho jaye ya right wing ho jaye, kuch

00:58:42.880 --> 00:58:51.880
[Guest]: bhi ho jaye then that's basically like the worst thing you can do to your art. Usse achcha

00:58:51.880 --> 00:58:55.880
[Guest]: hai ki aap chhod do, log khud samajh lenge kya politics and maybe it is flawed, maybe

00:58:55.880 --> 00:59:07.880
[Guest]: it is you know you're not aware of and better that is still a slightly better approach than

00:59:07.880 --> 00:59:14.880
[Guest]: like actually doing it in a very holistic manner.

00:59:14.880 --> 00:59:19.880
[Amit Varma]: That you know what you mentioned about Sanjay saying reminds me of that old quote that where

00:59:19.880 --> 00:59:23.880
[Amit Varma]: you stand depends on where you sit. So often we are just so much shaped by our circumstances

00:59:23.880 --> 00:59:27.880
[Amit Varma]: without even realizing it and I make a similar point about writing to my writing students

00:59:27.880 --> 00:59:32.880
[Amit Varma]: where I say that every piece is essentially a collection of choices and those choices

00:59:32.880 --> 00:59:36.880
[Amit Varma]: are affecting the reader in some way. Now you can either make all those choices yourself

00:59:36.880 --> 00:59:40.880
[Amit Varma]: and be intentional about it or they are just random things that have tumbled out of your

00:59:40.880 --> 00:59:45.880
[Amit Varma]: head and you're not in control. So you want to be in control but it is not that you know

00:59:45.880 --> 00:59:50.880
[Amit Varma]: by ignoring it that it the effects they have goes away and by the way that the roti thing

00:59:50.880 --> 00:59:55.880
[Amit Varma]: reminds me of an essay called I pencil by Leonard Reed. Have you read it? No. So I pencil

00:59:55.880 --> 01:00:00.880
[Amit Varma]: is this great sort of essay which talks about spontaneous order or how markets make things

01:00:00.880 --> 01:00:04.880
[Amit Varma]: happen without one central planner. So the point is it's from the first person account

01:00:04.880 --> 01:00:09.880
[Amit Varma]: of a pencil and all the different parts of a pencil coming from some 40-50 countries

01:00:09.880 --> 01:00:14.880
[Amit Varma]: and it's not like there is one master central planner who is deciding it. Just everyone

01:00:14.880 --> 01:00:19.880
[Amit Varma]: acts on their own individual incentives and magically without realizing it you have a

01:00:19.880 --> 01:00:24.880
[Unknown]: pencil and I think that was updated a few years ago where someone spoke of the iPhone

01:00:24.880 --> 01:00:28.880
[Amit Varma]: like that. How many different countries it comes from and I thought if maybe if Manikol

01:00:28.880 --> 01:00:33.880
[Amit Varma]: Ji was alive today instead of uski roti he would make meri roti and kind of do something.

01:00:33.880 --> 01:00:39.880
[Amit Varma]: No your point about politics and art is also I thought illustrated beautifully by something

01:00:39.880 --> 01:00:46.880
[Amit Varma]: like Masaan for example where the politics is invisible but at the same time you have

01:00:46.880 --> 01:00:51.880
[Amit Varma]: a Dalit character you are rooting for and a woman fighting oppression who you are rooting

01:00:51.880 --> 01:00:56.880
[Amit Varma]: for and you are rooting for these people and nothing is overt there is no bhasan bazi but

01:00:56.880 --> 01:01:02.880
[Amit Varma]: the very fact that readers who are not these people are rooting for them I think makes

01:01:02.880 --> 01:01:07.880
[Amit Varma]: a difference and my other thread which I want to go to which I keep coming back to during

01:01:07.880 --> 01:01:12.880
[Amit Varma]: the show is sort of the difference between the concrete and the abstract. Like I think

01:01:12.880 --> 01:01:18.880
[Amit Varma]: many of the things that tear our society apart are abstract notions like nationalism or purity

01:01:18.880 --> 01:01:24.880
[Amit Varma]: or race or caste or whatever and in the concrete we don't always act upon them. You know so

01:01:24.880 --> 01:01:29.880
[Amit Varma]: there is a common joke that a bigot will say oh I have a few Muslim friends but the irony

01:01:29.880 --> 01:01:33.880
[Amit Varma]: is he probably does and he is probably nice to them because in the concrete he has no

01:01:33.880 --> 01:01:39.880
[Amit Varma]: objection. It is those abstract conceptions that are the poison and that is where the

01:01:39.880 --> 01:01:44.880
[Amit Varma]: toxicity comes from and most of the time the worlds that we live in especially people who

01:01:44.880 --> 01:01:48.880
[Amit Varma]: are alive today is we are living more and more in an abstract world because even if

01:01:48.880 --> 01:01:53.880
[Amit Varma]: you are sitting with friends we are both looking into our smartphone if you are in a cafe together

01:01:53.880 --> 01:01:57.880
[Amit Varma]: right we are not talking to each other we are in this abstract world that is coming

01:01:57.880 --> 01:02:02.880
[Amit Varma]: to us from the smartphone instead of you know the flesh and blood person in front of us

01:02:02.880 --> 01:02:08.880
[Amit Varma]: and this is dangerous and I think one way in which the only way to really fight this

01:02:08.880 --> 01:02:13.880
[Amit Varma]: is to embrace the concrete a bit more and that is also what art does you know that is

01:02:13.880 --> 01:02:19.880
[Amit Varma]: what a good film or a good book or will do by putting you in somebody's head and making

01:02:19.880 --> 01:02:24.880
[Amit Varma]: them feel the way they do so that the other is no longer the other at least for that sort

01:02:24.880 --> 01:02:28.880
[Amit Varma]: of point in time. So I am just thinking a lot taking off from what you said because

01:02:28.880 --> 01:02:33.880
[Amit Varma]: I completely agree with that it kind of irritates me when the politics is overt because I think

01:02:33.880 --> 01:02:38.880
[Amit Varma]: it is most powerful when it does not need to be overt. Yeah though at the same time

01:02:38.880 --> 01:02:45.880
[Guest]: I understand in some cases representation is needed for people to feel empowered. So

01:02:45.880 --> 01:02:51.880
[Guest]: for example let's say Paranjeet or Nagraj Manjule when they make film about you know

01:02:51.880 --> 01:02:58.880
[Guest]: Dalit characters and characters who are oppressed and who are in the course of the film also

01:02:58.880 --> 01:03:05.880
[Guest]: face you know extreme violence because of their identity. So in yes in certain films

01:03:05.880 --> 01:03:11.880
[Guest]: and in certain cases yes that is required for people just to feel okay seen and feel

01:03:11.880 --> 01:03:18.880
[Guest]: that relatability and that anger is also needed. So yeah there are those kind of films but

01:03:18.880 --> 01:03:25.880
[Guest]: my point is mostly from from that position of privilege also but your position of an

01:03:25.880 --> 01:03:35.880
[Guest]: artist who is trying to yeah trying to make bridges in a way trying to reach across. So

01:03:35.880 --> 01:03:42.880
[Guest]: there are of course there are films that are just that just want you to feel seen and feel

01:03:42.880 --> 01:03:51.880
[Guest]: empowered about that okay this is my story this is my people who are kind of representing

01:03:51.880 --> 01:03:56.880
[Guest]: my anger against the system or against the oppressors and okay that is one kind of film

01:03:56.880 --> 01:04:07.880
[Guest]: but for me probably because I don't have that you know that natural anger. I don't have

01:04:07.880 --> 01:04:16.880
[Guest]: that having many reasons for that natural anger. So for me the job of an artist from

01:04:16.880 --> 01:04:27.880
[Guest]: yeah from a privileged community in this case Savarna Hindu male the job is to make bridges

01:04:27.880 --> 01:04:35.880
[Guest]: the job is to bring narratives which otherwise you won't see to see and to not feel like

01:04:35.880 --> 01:04:42.880
[Guest]: okay I'm I'm watching a political statement I'm watching a story and that story then starts

01:04:42.880 --> 01:04:48.880
[Guest]: living inside me which is exactly what happens with comedy also. So what comedy does I feel

01:04:48.880 --> 01:05:02.880
[Guest]: is it brings a very almost what evolution has given us this response to shocking things

01:05:02.880 --> 01:05:09.880
[Guest]: it's either laughter or you know or some kind of it is a sensory response and it is something

01:05:09.880 --> 01:05:16.880
[Guest]: you can't control. So for example in some of our shows though most of the people know

01:05:16.880 --> 01:05:31.880
[Guest]: what kind of show it is when they come to see me or see democracy on stage but still

01:05:31.880 --> 01:05:37.880
[Guest]: there are sometimes these 20-30% people who show up either because their friends have

01:05:37.880 --> 01:05:47.880
[Guest]: dragged them sometimes a lot of times it happens that people who live in America or UK and

01:05:47.880 --> 01:05:54.880
[Guest]: they send their parents to our shows like so these probably 30-year-old 40-year-olds

01:05:54.880 --> 01:05:59.880
[Guest]: they send their parents to our shows ticket le dete hain abhi parents ke aisaab se haan

01:05:59.880 --> 01:06:04.880
[Guest]: 500 rupee ka ticket liya hai to waste to nahi jaana chahiye to jao and they end up in our

01:06:04.880 --> 01:06:09.880
[Guest]: shows and then they discover that okay we are being very very political on stage but

01:06:09.880 --> 01:06:15.880
[Guest]: the thing then the advantage with comedy in comedy you can be directly political but you

01:06:15.880 --> 01:06:22.880
[Guest]: have a punchline and the thing is it's always a surprising punchline that is the point of

01:06:22.880 --> 01:06:28.880
[Guest]: the punchline it has to surprise you and the moment you are surprised you let down your

01:06:28.880 --> 01:06:34.880
[Guest]: guard because there is that emotion has kind of overtaken you it is either shock or surprise

01:06:34.880 --> 01:06:40.880
[Guest]: or sometimes the awe at the cleverness of the joke or something and you let your guard

01:06:40.880 --> 01:06:46.880
[Guest]: down and in that moment and then everyone around because as I said 70% people are already

01:06:46.880 --> 01:06:53.880
[Guest]: you know we are speaking to the choir kind of a thing and woh toh haste hain toh ek aur

01:06:53.880 --> 01:07:00.880
[Guest]: jo doosra natural response hai human human behavior ka which is you want to belong you

01:07:00.880 --> 01:07:07.880
[Guest]: always want to belong that's the core of religion and core of nationalism and everything and

01:07:07.880 --> 01:07:13.880
[Guest]: they want to belong in that room they start laughing and once you start laughing you kind

01:07:13.880 --> 01:07:25.880
[Guest]: of reduce the stature of these you know sacred figures you have ideas sometimes and sometimes

01:07:25.880 --> 01:07:30.880
[Guest]: it's people sometimes it's ideas sometimes it's certain incidents you can't really talk

01:07:30.880 --> 01:07:38.880
[Guest]: about that's what they have grown up with and they allow that so again so as artists

01:07:38.880 --> 01:07:46.880
[Guest]: I think our job is to create that bridge okay they may go back home and still never you know

01:07:46.880 --> 01:07:53.880
[Guest]: buy a ticket for our show again if they have a choice but thoda sa unke dimaag mein apne

01:07:53.880 --> 01:07:59.880
[Guest]: jo bhi sacred figures hai unki value thodi si kum ho gayi hai ki okay has sakte hain aur

01:07:59.880 --> 01:08:04.880
[Guest]: aisi koi buri baat nahi hai so that is what I think similarly the same thing we can do

01:08:04.880 --> 01:08:12.880
[Guest]: through cinema where you talk about certain things and you bring the kind of stories or

01:08:12.880 --> 01:08:20.880
[Guest]: the kind of dilemmas these people are facing the characters in the story to them and kabhi

01:08:20.880 --> 01:08:25.880
[Guest]: unhone ye socha nahi tha ki ye possible hai ki achha aisi bhi ek zindagi hoti hai aur wo

01:08:25.880 --> 01:08:30.880
[Guest]: zindagi jab aapne dekh li hai toh bhale hi aap us zindagi ya us tare ke insaan se aap

01:08:30.880 --> 01:08:35.880
[Guest]: nafrat karte hunge aapke dimaag mein bachpan se bataya gaya hai ki theek hai there is a

01:08:35.880 --> 01:08:42.880
[Guest]: certain you know caste or there are certain castes you can't interact with but you have

01:08:42.880 --> 01:08:47.880
[Guest]: interacted on screen you have interacted with that and with that person from that caste

01:08:47.880 --> 01:08:56.880
[Guest]: which you think is is really below your social standards and in for those 90 minutes you

01:08:56.880 --> 01:09:02.880
[Guest]: were actually as you said you would you are rooting for for the characters without really

01:09:02.880 --> 01:09:07.880
[Guest]: thinking about you know how you will behave with that character in real life and you meet

01:09:07.880 --> 01:09:14.880
[Guest]: them because then you will start identifying them for various tags you have given them

01:09:14.880 --> 01:09:25.880
[Guest]: to ultimately so in both the cases it is about asking people or kind of inviting people to

01:09:25.880 --> 01:09:33.880
[Guest]: lower their guards and and in some cases like in comedy almost forcing people to let down

01:09:33.880 --> 01:09:40.880
[Guest]: their guards and they do a lot of them and of course there are they have been cases they

01:09:40.880 --> 01:09:48.880
[Guest]: didn't and they kind of let it out because that shock or surprise or or whatever has

01:09:48.880 --> 01:09:53.880
[Guest]: to go somewhere so sometimes people kind of heckles that's why they heckle because they

01:09:53.880 --> 01:09:59.880
[Guest]: can't control this emotion they are dealing with it in that moment where people around

01:09:59.880 --> 01:10:04.880
[Guest]: them are laughing and they also want to laugh but their upbringing has told them it's not

01:10:04.880 --> 01:10:11.880
[Guest]: okay to laugh at this kind of a joke and so they don't know what to do with that that

01:10:11.880 --> 01:10:17.880
[Guest]: unresolved emotion at that time so they heckle and not just heckle they abuse and they sometimes

01:10:17.880 --> 01:10:24.880
[Guest]: we have met people at random places who kind of are really angry and want to just show

01:10:24.880 --> 01:10:32.880
[Guest]: that they are angry through whatever you know violent means they have chosen in that moment

01:10:32.880 --> 01:10:39.880
[Amit Varma]: so my sense of social media and tell me if I'm if you don't agree is that for all the

01:10:39.880 --> 01:10:44.880
[Amit Varma]: toxicity on Twitter and everywhere all the noise really comes from vocal minorities right

01:10:44.880 --> 01:10:49.880
[Amit Varma]: there are a few people who have chosen their tribe they'll make a lot of noise to signal

01:10:49.880 --> 01:10:53.880
[Amit Varma]: you know their virtue to their tribe and raise their status within the tribe and these are

01:10:53.880 --> 01:10:59.880
[Amit Varma]: tribes on all sides obviously but I believe that most people are like the silent majority

01:10:59.880 --> 01:11:03.880
[Amit Varma]: which is not saying anything because why get mobbed why get shouted down why get into this

01:11:03.880 --> 01:11:07.880
[Amit Varma]: shit but who are open to different points of view like when I do my writing class when

01:11:07.880 --> 01:11:12.880
[Amit Varma]: I tell people about writing opinion pieces what I always say is you always have to state

01:11:12.880 --> 01:11:18.880
[Amit Varma]: your opinion clearly but also take the strongest argument from the other side and state why

01:11:18.880 --> 01:11:22.880
[Amit Varma]: you disagree and one reason is of course that is an intellectually honest way to think about

01:11:22.880 --> 01:11:27.880
[Amit Varma]: anything but the other reason is that then the reader knows that if you're in the silent

01:11:27.880 --> 01:11:31.880
[Amit Varma]: majority the reader knows that this guy is not partisan she's not preaching to the choir

01:11:31.880 --> 01:11:36.880
[Amit Varma]: you know that I can trust her and that's important but but from what you're saying it almost

01:11:36.880 --> 01:11:41.880
[Amit Varma]: seems as if that it's it's not so much a silent majority but like you said

01:11:41.880 --> 01:11:43.880
[Amit Varma]: that scroll

01:11:51.880 --> 01:11:55.880
[Amit Varma]: but I would say that most people are actually kind of open to both they'll just go in whatever

01:11:55.880 --> 01:12:00.880
[Amit Varma]: this thing it's only these vocal minorities which have said that oh scroll is all left-wing

01:12:00.880 --> 01:12:06.880
[Amit Varma]: commies and so and so is whatever so what's would you agree or yeah but they are the leaders

01:12:06.880 --> 01:12:12.880
[Guest]: so the vocal people and they are always they are the natural reader leaders that's why

01:12:12.880 --> 01:12:20.880
[Guest]: they are you know so vocal so fearlessly and all right now what is happening and probably

01:12:20.880 --> 01:12:30.880
[Guest]: what was always happening is the state always acts as as the father of this joint family

01:12:30.880 --> 01:12:48.880
[Guest]: and they choose to ask I mean all these things basically this patriarch of the family is

01:12:48.880 --> 01:13:00.880
[Guest]: deciding now and which has always been the case is there are these local enforcers of

01:13:00.880 --> 01:13:06.880
[Guest]: this patriarch and at some point the enforcers try to put stuff which they believe in and

01:13:06.880 --> 01:13:10.880
[Guest]: they don't even need to take approval from the patriarch and which is what is happening

01:13:10.880 --> 01:13:16.880
[Guest]: right now in on on most of the social media where there are people who are of course who

01:13:16.880 --> 01:13:24.880
[Guest]: know that they won't be reprimanded or stopped by by the bosses to do whatever they want

01:13:24.880 --> 01:13:31.880
[Guest]: to do so they can you know announce on on social media okay this person has said this

01:13:31.880 --> 01:13:39.880
[Guest]: particular thing which is really offensive and that's it and now just go and you know

01:13:39.880 --> 01:13:46.880
[Guest]: abuse them or file cases against them or whatever the multiple ways of destroying their lives

01:13:46.880 --> 01:13:56.880
[Guest]: so they are getting power from both sides from above from where no one is stopping them

01:13:56.880 --> 01:14:03.880
[Guest]: and from whom they are speaking because they are getting the response so that silent majority

01:14:03.880 --> 01:14:10.880
[Guest]: thing I don't really think that's a thing anymore there is no silent majority they are

01:14:10.880 --> 01:14:19.880
[Guest]: all vocal in whatever sometimes vocal in their silence also or their you know vocal in their

01:14:19.880 --> 01:14:26.880
[Guest]: in their choices that they still they may not abuse but they are supporting the people

01:14:26.880 --> 01:14:34.880
[Guest]: who are or they are having completely normal relations with people who are calling for

01:14:34.880 --> 01:14:41.880
[Guest]: you know all kinds of violent crimes against people who are who don't believe or who don't

01:14:41.880 --> 01:14:46.880
[Guest]: agree with them so I don't think that silent majority of concept

01:14:46.880 --> 01:14:57.880
[Guest]: I don't know is it a saving grace or not but yeah this yeah still it is probably a saving

01:14:57.880 --> 01:15:12.880
[Guest]: grace that a lot of these people who are listening to this vocal angry group would probably be

01:15:12.880 --> 01:15:18.880
[Guest]: doing their normal life stuff if they were not you know they won't really take the lead

01:15:18.880 --> 01:15:25.880
[Guest]: so that's the only probably saving grace they won't take the lead they will someday they

01:15:25.880 --> 01:15:31.880
[Guest]: are very happy to be part of the mob and if there is a leader telling them what to do

01:15:31.880 --> 01:15:37.880
[Guest]: they will happily do it but without a leader they'll probably be lost or they'll probably

01:15:37.880 --> 01:15:46.880
[Guest]: go back to okay finding finding whatever better jobs better life whatever and for now they

01:15:46.880 --> 01:15:51.880
