[Guest]: So, because of that they are creating lots of new stuff and I like that.

03:29:20.380 --> 03:29:24.380
[Amit Varma]: You mentioned, you know, sometimes replacing the rice in your pulao with something else.

03:29:24.380 --> 03:29:27.380
[Amit Varma]: And I remembered I was in Athens earlier this year

03:29:27.380 --> 03:29:30.380
[Amit Varma]: and we were just walking on the road.

03:29:30.380 --> 03:29:36.380
[Amit Varma]: So, we were damn tired, too tired to go to Google and look up what is a high rated restaurant or whatever.

03:29:36.380 --> 03:29:41.380
[Amit Varma]: So, we just saw, there was a small quiet hole in the wall kind of place called Elevoro which we entered.

03:29:41.380 --> 03:29:45.380
[Amit Varma]: And I just, I was too tired to look at the menu properly.

03:29:45.380 --> 03:29:47.380
[Amit Varma]: I ordered something called a Veal Kritharaki.

03:29:47.380 --> 03:29:49.380
[Amit Varma]: One of the best dishes I have ever had.

03:29:49.380 --> 03:29:54.380
[Amit Varma]: And Kritharaki apparently is a kind of pasta which looks like rice.

03:29:54.380 --> 03:29:57.380
[Guest]: Okay, I have seen that part.

03:29:57.380 --> 03:30:00.380
[Amit Varma]: I think even the Italians have a version called Orzo or something.

03:30:00.380 --> 03:30:03.380
[Amit Varma]: But this was a Greek version and it wasn't the Veal itself.

03:30:03.380 --> 03:30:08.380
[Amit Varma]: It was just a Kritharaki and it was all the veg preparation with tomatoes and different things.

03:30:08.380 --> 03:30:10.380
[Amit Varma]: And it was so incredibly delicious.

03:30:10.380 --> 03:30:12.380
[Amit Varma]: My friend was in Athens after a week.

03:30:12.380 --> 03:30:13.380
[Amit Varma]: He asked me where to eat.

03:30:13.380 --> 03:30:15.380
[Amit Varma]: I said, go here, order this.

03:30:15.380 --> 03:30:19.380
[Amit Varma]: He ordered that and later messaged me and said, Amit, the best rice I have ever had.

03:30:19.380 --> 03:30:24.380
[Amit Varma]: So, in that particular meal, I loved so much, I was mindful through every bite.

03:30:24.380 --> 03:30:27.380
[Amit Varma]: But my other thing I try to watch out for is sometimes,

03:30:27.380 --> 03:30:31.380
[Amit Varma]: I am like many of your guests you are complaining about when you feed them.

03:30:31.380 --> 03:30:32.380
[Amit Varma]: That I am just absent-minded.

03:30:32.380 --> 03:30:36.380
[Amit Varma]: I am lost in conversation or I am reading something and I won't even notice the food.

03:30:36.380 --> 03:30:39.380
[Amit Varma]: Like you put a meat dish in front of me, I will eat the whole thing.

03:30:39.380 --> 03:30:43.380
[Amit Varma]: You will ask if it was lamb or mutton.

03:30:43.380 --> 03:30:47.380
[Amit Varma]: And I won't remember because I would have not paid attention to that.

03:30:47.380 --> 03:30:49.380
[Unknown]: And that is something I try to fight.

03:30:49.380 --> 03:30:52.380
[Amit Varma]: And you have mentioned and meditation is a way of fighting that.

03:30:52.380 --> 03:30:54.380
[Amit Varma]: And you mentioned that cooking is like meditation.

03:30:54.380 --> 03:31:02.380
[Amit Varma]: Do you consciously try to bring that quality of being mindful to the present moment and other things also to things you do?

03:31:02.380 --> 03:31:06.380
[Amit Varma]: Is it something that has happened over time or you were always like this?

03:31:06.380 --> 03:31:08.380
[Guest]: No, I think it has happened over time.

03:31:08.380 --> 03:31:15.380
[Guest]: Because at some point, I think I realized in those initial years of trying to be a writer.

03:31:15.380 --> 03:31:18.380
[Guest]: I realized two things.

03:31:18.380 --> 03:31:27.380
[Guest]: One, there is nothing called merit or God-gifted talent or something like that.

03:31:27.380 --> 03:31:29.380
[Guest]: There is only one thing that is discipline.

03:31:29.380 --> 03:31:38.380
[Guest]: And it's only discipline which can create magic and make it look effortless.

03:31:38.380 --> 03:31:46.380
[Guest]: So, from there, I started paying attention to every little thing.

03:31:46.380 --> 03:31:53.380
[Guest]: Except maybe the only thing I still don't pay attention to is the clothes I wear.

03:31:53.380 --> 03:31:57.380
[Guest]: Clothes I kind of select or buy or something.

03:31:57.380 --> 03:31:59.380
[Guest]: In that, my mind still doesn't work.

03:31:59.380 --> 03:32:01.380
[Guest]: I have not interacted with that world at all.

03:32:01.380 --> 03:32:11.380
[Guest]: But otherwise, yes, food, reading, listening to music, watching movies, walking in a city, something I completely love.

03:32:11.380 --> 03:32:13.380
[Guest]: I just love walking.

03:32:13.380 --> 03:32:21.380
[Guest]: Even in Bombay, I have walked so many times in those six years period, especially 2004 to 2010.

03:32:21.380 --> 03:32:37.380
[Guest]: I would walk from this place, four bungalows or Andheri, Versova to Kandivali East, almost three hours of walking, 12 kilometers or so.

03:32:37.380 --> 03:32:44.380
[Guest]: And it was very, very cathartic and very, very kind of it would put me in a zone.

03:32:44.380 --> 03:32:51.380
[Guest]: Suddenly, the traffic, it was traffic jammed like end to end at that time and there was so much noise on the street.

03:32:51.380 --> 03:32:58.380
[Guest]: But it still would put me in a very peaceful state of mind, just walking.

03:32:58.380 --> 03:33:01.380
[Guest]: And always there's something new to see on the road.

03:33:01.380 --> 03:33:06.380
[Guest]: Always there are even the same road, same whatever locations.

03:33:06.380 --> 03:33:10.380
[Guest]: And every day there would be so many new experiences.

03:33:10.380 --> 03:33:14.380
[Guest]: And those experiences were so fulfilling for me.

03:33:14.380 --> 03:33:15.380
[Guest]: And they still are.

03:33:15.380 --> 03:33:20.380
[Guest]: I mean, I still make it a point to walk as much as I can in the city.

03:33:20.380 --> 03:33:26.380
[Guest]: Though Bombay is one of probably the worst cities to walk in, in terms of there are no walking spaces.

03:33:26.380 --> 03:33:28.380
[Guest]: The traffic is bad.

03:33:28.380 --> 03:33:32.380
[Guest]: It's so polluted and really there are no pavements left.

03:33:32.380 --> 03:33:35.380
[Guest]: There are pavements, but then there is so much encroachment happening.

03:33:35.380 --> 03:33:43.380
[Guest]: And then encroachment is also kind of a systemic, this thing that they are not given enough space where they can actually put up their stalls.

03:33:43.380 --> 03:33:45.380
[Guest]: So they are on the pavement.

03:33:45.380 --> 03:33:53.380
[Guest]: And people are generally very rude to or unmindful of pedestrians.

03:33:53.380 --> 03:34:06.380
[Guest]: It's very difficult to cross the road when you have a signal, even if the signal is red for vehicles and you have that green walking sign.

03:34:06.380 --> 03:34:10.380
[Guest]: Even at that time, you are afraid that someone or the other can hit you.

03:34:10.380 --> 03:34:15.380
[Guest]: Because a lot of people, especially at that time, want to go fast.

03:34:15.380 --> 03:34:23.380
[Guest]: So it has happened a couple of times where I have kind of been lucky to not been, I have been hit while walking on the road.

03:34:23.380 --> 03:34:32.380
[Guest]: And I kind of had like a mini fracture in my rib because someone hit me, a vehicle and all.

03:34:32.380 --> 03:34:38.380
[Guest]: So all that has happened, but of course, it's part of whatever it is, part of living in India.

03:34:38.380 --> 03:34:53.380
[Guest]: So no complaints, but otherwise, yeah, I want to kind of be mindful of every moment in every way.

03:34:53.380 --> 03:34:58.380
[Amit Varma]: So a couple of questions rolled into one in the sense a couple of themes I've explored in the past.

03:34:58.380 --> 03:35:07.380
[Amit Varma]: And one of them is I was chatting with, I had breakfast with a friend of mine in Bangalore, who's also a friend of yours.

03:35:07.380 --> 03:35:10.380
[Amit Varma]: I'll tell you who after this episode.

03:35:10.380 --> 03:35:16.380
[Amit Varma]: And he's a CXO position person at a major company.

03:35:16.380 --> 03:35:24.380
[Amit Varma]: And he was complaining that when he goes out for dinner or lunch with his colleagues, who are all senior people in the company, there's nothing to talk about.

03:35:24.380 --> 03:35:28.380
[Amit Varma]: Because they don't read books, they don't watch movies, there's no interior life.

03:35:28.380 --> 03:35:32.380
[Amit Varma]: Everything is, you know, the straight and narrow, what they kind of do.

03:35:32.380 --> 03:35:44.380
[Amit Varma]: Which also leads me to thinking is that by a process of self selection, the people we choose to hang out with, we often imagine that everybody is like us, that they're into books and music and they have that kind of interior life.

03:35:44.380 --> 03:35:47.380
[Amit Varma]: And but a lot of people, you know, simply don't.

03:35:47.380 --> 03:35:48.380
[Amit Varma]: And this is one strand.

03:35:48.380 --> 03:36:00.380
[Amit Varma]: And the other strand is something I've brought up because it's made me introspect a lot, which is this book I read called Wanting by Luke Burgess, where the primary theme of the book is that a lot of what we want.

03:36:00.380 --> 03:36:08.380
[Amit Varma]: And he got this concept from a philosopher called Rene Girard, who was asked to teach a class on literature a few decades ago.

03:36:08.380 --> 03:36:09.380
[Amit Varma]: And he was a philosopher.

03:36:09.380 --> 03:36:11.380
[Amit Varma]: But he said, okay, I'll do it.

03:36:11.380 --> 03:36:13.380
[Amit Varma]: He read the books he was supposed to read.

03:36:13.380 --> 03:36:19.380
[Amit Varma]: And he found that all the characters in those books, they wanted something only because somebody else wanted it.

03:36:19.380 --> 03:36:21.380
[Amit Varma]: So he coined the term mimetic desire.

03:36:21.380 --> 03:36:22.380
[Amit Varma]: Right.

03:36:22.380 --> 03:36:26.380
[Amit Varma]: So a mimetic desire would be that I want a Mercedes because, you know, it's a done thing.

03:36:26.380 --> 03:36:29.380
[Amit Varma]: Or a young person may say, I want to get married and have kids.

03:36:29.380 --> 03:36:30.380
[Amit Varma]: Why?

03:36:30.380 --> 03:36:31.380
[Amit Varma]: Because it's the expected route.

03:36:31.380 --> 03:36:32.380
[Amit Varma]: Right.

03:36:32.380 --> 03:36:35.380
[Amit Varma]: And the term Burgess used for this was thick desires and thin desires.

03:36:35.380 --> 03:36:40.380
[Amit Varma]: So thick desires are something that you intrinsically want deep inside.

03:36:40.380 --> 03:36:42.380
[Unknown]: It's coming from nowhere.

03:36:42.380 --> 03:36:44.380
[Amit Varma]: And obviously creature comforts are taken for granted.

03:36:44.380 --> 03:36:46.380
[Amit Varma]: So we're not talking about eating and all.

03:36:46.380 --> 03:36:54.380
[Amit Varma]: Thin desires are desires which come from something around you, like the Mercedes, like the I want to get married and have kids kind of thing.

03:36:54.380 --> 03:36:55.380
[Amit Varma]: Those are thin desires.

03:36:55.380 --> 03:36:59.380
[Amit Varma]: And the strange thing is that thin desires can be really intense.

03:36:59.380 --> 03:37:00.380
[Unknown]: Right.

03:37:00.380 --> 03:37:02.380
[Amit Varma]: And thick desires can be hidden in the background.

03:37:02.380 --> 03:37:04.380
[Amit Varma]: So you don't even know what it is.

03:37:04.380 --> 03:37:10.380
[Amit Varma]: For example, when you're a young writer, the thin desire could be that I want to be a writer.

03:37:10.380 --> 03:37:11.380
[Amit Varma]: You're chasing the glamour of writing.

03:37:11.380 --> 03:37:12.380
[Amit Varma]: Right.

03:37:12.380 --> 03:37:15.380
[Amit Varma]: That I'll get this prize, he'll do that, people will come to listen to me.

03:37:15.380 --> 03:37:23.380
[Amit Varma]: But hidden behind that, there might be also a thick desire to write, to create, to tell stories and all of that.

03:37:23.380 --> 03:37:28.380
[Amit Varma]: And you know, when you talk about your time in Pune, where you worked in a software company, Canvay, for a few months,

03:37:28.380 --> 03:37:36.380
[Amit Varma]: and you pointed out that what made you decide to leave was when you looked at all your seniors who have worked there for 10 years,

03:37:36.380 --> 03:37:38.380
[Amit Varma]: and you said, in 10 years, I am this.

03:37:38.380 --> 03:37:39.380
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

03:37:39.380 --> 03:37:44.380
[Amit Varma]: And you fought that thin desire, that I'll have a flat, a family, this and that.

03:37:44.380 --> 03:37:50.380
[Amit Varma]: You fought that thin desire, and you went out to look for something else.

03:37:50.380 --> 03:37:56.380
[Amit Varma]: And it's very hard, I think, when we are young, and I find it hard to answer even now,

03:37:56.380 --> 03:38:00.380
[Amit Varma]: though I can do it much better than I could have 10 years ago, that what are our thick desires?

03:38:00.380 --> 03:38:05.380
[Amit Varma]: Because most people don't have to go back to the first strand, that interior life,

03:38:05.380 --> 03:38:09.380
[Amit Varma]: and therefore, that possibility of self-reflecting.

03:38:09.380 --> 03:38:13.380
[Amit Varma]: Who am I? What do I want? Why do I want the things that I do?

03:38:13.380 --> 03:38:15.380
[Amit Varma]: Why am I sort of on this path?

03:38:15.380 --> 03:38:21.380
[Amit Varma]: You know, and again, these two seem connected to me for that reason.

03:38:21.380 --> 03:38:26.380
[Amit Varma]: So, what is your sense? Because you had that self-reflection to be able to take a step back,

03:38:26.380 --> 03:38:29.380
[Amit Varma]: to look at these people and say, I don't want to be like this, I don't want this.

03:38:29.380 --> 03:38:36.380
[Amit Varma]: And you could also then not join the FTIR course you got in for because you were like, no, I don't want this.

03:38:36.380 --> 03:38:42.380
[Amit Varma]: So, if you have to think about your thick desires, like, you know, maybe 10 years later, you wake up in the morning,

03:38:42.380 --> 03:38:45.380
[Amit Varma]: what do you do? And that's perhaps a superficial question.

03:38:45.380 --> 03:38:51.380
[Amit Varma]: You can tell me surface things like, I will cook pulao in my 190th recipe or whatever.

03:38:51.380 --> 03:38:56.380
[Amit Varma]: But in general, when you think of your thick desires, you know, an outsider can guess,

03:38:56.380 --> 03:39:00.380
[Amit Varma]: that there will be storytelling, but how do you look at this?

03:39:00.380 --> 03:39:03.380
[Amit Varma]: And I'm sure you've thought about variants of this question for yourself.

03:39:03.380 --> 03:39:15.380
[Guest]: No, I have not actually. For me, I can't even think about tomorrow.

03:39:15.380 --> 03:39:24.380
[Guest]: So, that's a bit of, I don't know, it's a handicap or something or a blessing, I don't know.

03:39:24.380 --> 03:39:28.380
[Guest]: But for me, it's always difficult to see the future.

03:39:28.380 --> 03:39:40.380
[Guest]: So, whatever the desire is, it's very, it's just making sure that the present is present for me.

03:39:40.380 --> 03:39:46.380
[Guest]: And in my childhood, I had a desire to become a writer.

03:39:46.380 --> 03:39:52.380
[Guest]: But those are very, very broad kind of desires, that I want to go into writing.

03:39:52.380 --> 03:39:58.380
[Guest]: There was probably at some point, the idea of glamour also, that there is a film industry.

03:39:58.380 --> 03:40:05.380
[Guest]: After that, when I came here, the glamour of the film industry must have gone away in a week.

03:40:05.380 --> 03:40:12.380
[Guest]: But there was always that thing that you can write and create a magic.

03:40:12.380 --> 03:40:18.380
[Guest]: Where it is again, all of these processes, cooking or writing, both are equally magical processes,

03:40:18.380 --> 03:40:25.380
[Guest]: where you are just black ink on white paper, and you are transported to another world,

03:40:25.380 --> 03:40:35.380
[Guest]: and you start seeing these images in your head, and you start caring for people who don't even exist,

03:40:35.380 --> 03:40:40.380
[Guest]: who are in someone else's head, and you are caring for them, and you're crying for them.

03:40:40.380 --> 03:40:50.380
[Guest]: So, I read Gunahon Ka Devta for the first time, Dharamveer Bharti's epic, one of the most celebrated novels in Hindi.

03:40:50.380 --> 03:40:55.380
[Guest]: So, I started reading Gunahon Ka Devta in college, I was probably in second year.

03:40:55.380 --> 03:41:01.380
[Guest]: And there were going to be holidays, I started reading during the exam time.

03:41:01.380 --> 03:41:05.380
[Guest]: I couldn't put it down during the exams also,

03:41:05.380 --> 03:41:12.380
[Guest]: at that time I was quite into, I didn't want to, flunk is a far-fetched thing,

03:41:12.380 --> 03:41:18.380
[Guest]: I didn't want to be below the top three rankers in the class, so I wanted to be among the top three.

03:41:18.380 --> 03:41:21.380
[Guest]: And I was studying very seriously at that time,

03:41:21.380 --> 03:41:25.380
[Guest]: even then I got the novel in my hand, and I started reading, and through the exam,

03:41:25.380 --> 03:41:28.380
[Guest]: I was preparing for two hours at night, after that I took out an hour and was reading,

03:41:28.380 --> 03:41:36.380
[Guest]: and the exam got over, and there were some 20-25 pages left at the end, and at some point I didn't want to finish,

03:41:36.380 --> 03:41:42.380
[Guest]: I was like, if it gets over, then what will I do, but I cared so much for Sudha and Chandra, the characters.

03:41:42.380 --> 03:41:48.380
[Guest]: And when the last 20-25 pages were left, that day I had to take the Lucknow train from Banaras,

03:41:48.380 --> 03:41:53.380
[Guest]: so I thought, okay, let's do it, let's go home, I'll read in the train.

03:41:53.380 --> 03:42:00.380
[Guest]: And when the train got over, I was at Top Birds, the Kashi-Vishwanath Express used to run from Banaras,

03:42:00.380 --> 03:42:06.380
[Guest]: and there was a box in that train, S6, which used to be called Lucknow-Bhogi,

03:42:06.380 --> 03:42:12.380
[Guest]: and all its reservations were from Lucknow, the Lucknow-Delhi train, so it was Banaras-Delhi train.

03:42:12.380 --> 03:42:16.380
[Guest]: So that box used to get empty in Banaras-Lucknow, so most of the students used to go in that,

03:42:16.380 --> 03:42:21.380
[Guest]: taking a non-reserved ticket in a reserved bogie, because it was empty till Lucknow.

03:42:21.380 --> 03:42:30.380
[Guest]: So I was sitting on top of that, and that novel got over, and it stabbed me like anything,

03:42:30.380 --> 03:42:35.380
[Guest]: when it ended on the note, and on the note it ended.

03:42:35.380 --> 03:42:45.380
[Guest]: And probably for the next two hours of the journey, I was crying like I have lost a very close friend in an accident,

03:42:45.380 --> 03:42:53.380
[Guest]: like I was in shock, I was in pain, I cried for two hours, and people, so many people were concerned,

03:42:53.380 --> 03:42:59.380
[Guest]: were strangers, they kept asking me what happened, then probably at some point they made up their own reasons,

03:42:59.380 --> 03:43:04.380
[Guest]: that maybe there was a break-up, maybe something happened, maybe there was a tragedy at home,

03:43:04.380 --> 03:43:09.380
[Guest]: I couldn't even explain to them that I am crying because of this book in my hand.

03:43:09.380 --> 03:43:23.380
[Guest]: But at that point, I kind of, I think subconsciously at least, I figured that this is a very powerful medium,

03:43:23.380 --> 03:43:31.380
[Guest]: storytelling, and I want to be a part of this tribe that can create these very strong emotions,

03:43:31.380 --> 03:43:39.380
[Guest]: and give them, give people some kind of catharsis, maybe this line,

03:43:39.380 --> 03:43:44.380
[Guest]: Kaun rota hai, kisi aur ki khati rahe do, sabko apni kisi baat pe rona aaya.

03:43:44.380 --> 03:43:49.380
[Guest]: So ultimately, you are, probably I was crying for some other, whatever, my own traumas,

03:43:49.380 --> 03:44:00.380
[Guest]: but it was connected to Sudhan Chandra's journey, and so to be able to be an entertainer,

03:44:00.380 --> 03:44:09.380
[Guest]: and a therapist, and a magician at the same time, I think it was something which I found slowly,

03:44:09.380 --> 03:44:17.380
[Guest]: I kind of figured that's really, really fascinating and good challenge to have in life.

03:44:17.380 --> 03:44:26.380
[Guest]: So probably that was the only thick desire I can kind of talk about, I can think of ki haan, wo tha shayad.

03:44:26.380 --> 03:44:37.380
[Guest]: Uske alawa mujhe nahi pata aur thin desires, I kind of, I'm aware of, and I'm constantly like pushing them back.

03:44:37.380 --> 03:44:45.380
[Guest]: I know ki theek hai, car jab mene dekha ki sabke paas car hai, toh phir mere dimaag ne bola ki car toh kitne logon ke paas hai.

03:44:45.380 --> 03:44:51.380
[Guest]: Toh car acquire karna toh bekaar, matlab ekdum hi bekaar ka ambition hai,

03:44:51.380 --> 03:44:57.380
[Guest]: kyonki wo toh itne logon ke paas hai ki, of course, not all of them really,

03:44:57.380 --> 03:45:06.380
[Guest]: if car is something you get only when you deserve it, I don't think so many people deserve having a car.

03:45:06.380 --> 03:45:14.380
[Guest]: So then it's, there is a problem in the calculation or in what the theory is that car is a symbol of success.

03:45:14.380 --> 03:45:22.380
[Guest]: My parents still think that, they keep asking me, car kab loge hai, abhi ghar le liya tumne, car le lo,

03:45:22.380 --> 03:45:27.380
[Guest]: because in their head it is still incomplete, that picture of whatever, their idea of success.

03:45:27.380 --> 03:45:37.380
[Guest]: Ki theek hai, baaki sab cheezein, aap kuchh likh rahe hain and you are happy in what you are doing, but that symbol is still attached.

03:45:37.380 --> 03:45:44.380
[Guest]: Similarly, for kids, like having a kid, we decided not to have kids because, again,

03:45:44.380 --> 03:45:50.380
[Guest]: that's probably the easiest thing to do in the world and everyone has, you know,

03:45:50.380 --> 03:45:55.380
[Guest]: whatever has procreated through generations and that's why we are here.

03:45:55.380 --> 03:46:05.380
[Guest]: But it's definitely, I don't even understand, car, I can still understand as a symbol of success in some ways.

03:46:05.380 --> 03:46:14.380
[Guest]: How does having a kid, of course, I mean, there are people who might feel fulfilled and who might really feel that way,

03:46:14.380 --> 03:46:27.380
[Guest]: but to attach a sense of failure or incompletion to people who don't have kids by choice or by whatever,

03:46:27.380 --> 03:46:32.380
[Guest]: by some kind of compulsions is a very strange idea to take root.

03:46:32.380 --> 03:46:42.380
[Guest]: I don't understand how that is a failure if something which can be done so easily biologically,

03:46:42.380 --> 03:46:58.380
[Guest]: how is that a major achievement if it's just one molecule of semen interacting with one molecule of ova.

03:46:58.380 --> 03:47:07.380
[Amit Varma]: Like one of the themes I think about sometimes is how we are the only animals who are wired to fight their own wiring.

03:47:07.380 --> 03:47:13.380
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, we are programmed in certain ways to have kids, do this, do that, but we are also wired to be rational.

03:47:13.380 --> 03:47:17.380
[Amit Varma]: That's one level above that. And we can fight our own wiring. We can decide that I won't be tribal.

03:47:17.380 --> 03:47:24.380
[Amit Varma]: I won't have kids. I won't have whatever. I once wrote a provocative column about why it is immoral to have children.

03:47:24.380 --> 03:47:29.380
[Amit Varma]: That was a headline and the kind of trolling I got from parents everywhere who took it personally,

03:47:29.380 --> 03:47:33.380
[Amit Varma]: which I didn't, you know, kind of expect that way.

03:47:33.380 --> 03:47:39.380
[Amit Varma]: It's, you know, it's a backlash of what Paul Graham calls the aggressively conventional minded,

03:47:39.380 --> 03:47:44.380
[Amit Varma]: which is a phrase I love, aggressively conventional minded.

03:47:44.380 --> 03:47:49.380
[Amit Varma]: Let's, you know, we've got like 20 minutes left. I feel like we should talk for another five, six hours,

03:47:49.380 --> 03:47:58.380
[Amit Varma]: but I know you got to get back home and all of that. I want to talk about, you know, you mentioned 2006 to 2010,

03:47:58.380 --> 03:48:01.380
[Amit Varma]: what you learned in those years, your struggle in Bollywood.

03:48:01.380 --> 03:48:09.380
[Amit Varma]: And I'm also sort of interested in different places where you have spoken about, say, firstly, the centrality of Satya.

03:48:09.380 --> 03:48:12.380
[Amit Varma]: You've said that if there was no Satya, there would be no Masaan.

03:48:12.380 --> 03:48:19.380
[Amit Varma]: Because ripple effect ki tarah Satya se a certain kind of filmmaking was enabled and Anurag Kashyap came out of that.

03:48:19.380 --> 03:48:23.380
[Amit Varma]: And Anurag Kashyap was a big part in nurturing his own little ecosystem of people.

03:48:23.380 --> 03:48:26.380
[Amit Varma]: Both you and Neeraj worked with him and met through there.

03:48:26.380 --> 03:48:33.380
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, this is a question I often ask historians on my show, but it seems pertinent to ask you as well that,

03:48:33.380 --> 03:48:38.380
[Amit Varma]: you know, Thomas Carlyle came up with what he called the great man theory of history, which is very contentious.

03:48:38.380 --> 03:48:45.380
[Amit Varma]: Great man theory of history is that history is made by great men and in Carlyle's time, obviously, great men, but you get it, great people.

03:48:45.380 --> 03:48:50.380
[Amit Varma]: That somebody comes and changes everything and history proceeds differently.

03:48:50.380 --> 03:48:57.380
[Amit Varma]: And people who criticize this theory say that, no, it's wrong that we are giving too much importance to individuals.

03:48:57.380 --> 03:49:03.380
[Amit Varma]: Jo hona tha, hona tha, you know, trends go in a particular direction and then whatever has to happen has to happen.

03:49:03.380 --> 03:49:11.380
[Amit Varma]: Now, when I think of individuals through history, like I won't use great in a qualitative sense, like great, great, but people who've had a big impact.

03:49:11.380 --> 03:49:15.380
[Amit Varma]: I think individuals and accidents play a huge part.

03:49:15.380 --> 03:49:21.380
[Amit Varma]: Ki, you know, satya was perhaps something that came about because of a bunch of different circumstances.

03:49:21.380 --> 03:49:24.380
[Amit Varma]: And I've had an episode on Uday Bhatia on satya as well.

03:49:24.380 --> 03:49:30.380
[Amit Varma]: And maybe there were other lucky accidents which could have taken us in a different direction, which didn't happen.

03:49:30.380 --> 03:49:34.380
[Amit Varma]: Or some could make that argument ki ye to hona hi tha, satya nahi hota toh aur kuchh hota.

03:49:34.380 --> 03:49:37.380
[Amit Varma]: Anurag nahi aata toh kuchh aur hota. Or he would have been enabled by something else.

03:49:37.380 --> 03:49:39.380
[Amit Varma]: Toh ye sab ho hi jaata.

03:49:39.380 --> 03:49:46.380
[Amit Varma]: So, couple of questions. And the first question is that broadly, what do you think of this?

03:49:46.380 --> 03:49:53.380
[Amit Varma]: Because I feel that too often we don't appreciate how random everything is.

03:49:53.380 --> 03:49:57.380
[Amit Varma]: Right? Aapne pehle merit ki baat ki. You know, good things will happen.

03:49:57.380 --> 03:50:00.380
[Amit Varma]: People will say aarey maine kiya aur bad things will happen. They'll let it get them down.

03:50:00.380 --> 03:50:05.380
[Amit Varma]: Self-esteem effect ho jaata hai. Whereas actually 99% of everything is sheer dumb luck.

03:50:05.380 --> 03:50:09.380
[Amit Varma]: Right? Toh ye bhi do lucky cheez ho gaye. Unke ye impacts huye.

03:50:09.380 --> 03:50:14.380
[Amit Varma]: It is not that there is a larger teleological narrative ki, you know, ki ek plan hai.

03:50:14.380 --> 03:50:16.380
[Amit Varma]: Toh aapke kya thoughts hai iske baare mein?

03:50:16.380 --> 03:50:26.380
[Guest]: Yes, I do believe strongly in the randomness of things rather than like you could have planned like certain things.

03:50:26.380 --> 03:50:33.380
[Guest]: And I think ek aur cheez jo main, about cinema I say, but probably true for almost all the things in life.

03:50:33.380 --> 03:50:43.380
[Guest]: Good films happen always by accident. Bad films happen always by design.

03:50:43.380 --> 03:50:45.380
[Guest]: Beautiful.

03:50:45.380 --> 03:50:56.380
[Guest]: You always, like, agar aapko film banane mein bahut, agar aapne bola, bahut mahinat ki hai, toh phir aapne shayad kharab film hi banayi hai. Kyunki mahinat se nahi banti hai.

03:50:56.380 --> 03:51:01.380
[Guest]: In fact, kharab film banane mein zyada mahinat lagti hai. Main ye bhi maanta hu.

03:51:01.380 --> 03:51:05.380
[Guest]: Achi film banane mein kam mahinat lagti hai. Because again, luck is on your side.

03:51:05.380 --> 03:51:08.380
[Guest]: And then there are many, many factors you can't control.

03:51:08.380 --> 03:51:15.380
[Guest]: Sometimes it's the time, sometimes it's so many like things which happen.

03:51:15.380 --> 03:51:28.380
[Guest]: And I'm again using film as an example of or as a parallel to our real life because there are so many elements which help create a person like someone is called great.

03:51:28.380 --> 03:51:30.380
[Guest]: But how does that great happen?

03:51:30.380 --> 03:51:37.380
[Guest]: Because there are so many factors which are completely out of control of that great person which made them great.

03:51:37.380 --> 03:51:41.380
[Guest]: Toh randomness kaafi zyada hai universe mein.

03:51:41.380 --> 03:51:51.380
[Guest]: And just because we can't, that's one part of our wiring, which is still, I think, primitive.

03:51:51.380 --> 03:51:55.380
[Guest]: We don't accept randomness.

03:51:55.380 --> 03:52:00.380
[Guest]: We are baffled by it and we want to find patterns.

03:52:00.380 --> 03:52:15.380
[Guest]: And those patterns have created, so that search for patterns has given rise to this idea of people we trust.

03:52:15.380 --> 03:52:27.380
[Guest]: And then those people we trust, mostly historians or, you know, who have found patterns and who select certain patterns to say, OK, certain things were great or certain men were great.

03:52:27.380 --> 03:52:35.380
[Guest]: And then those people then create further patterns which are, let's say, the great people effecting great changes.

03:52:35.380 --> 03:52:39.380
[Guest]: So, mera toh wahi maanna hai.

03:52:39.380 --> 03:52:52.380
[Guest]: Aur ussi wajah se again that idea of merit is highly, it's not just flawed, it's completely, I would say, bullshit, the idea of merit.

03:52:52.380 --> 03:53:00.380
[Guest]: Kyunki bahut saara usme luck hai. Aur phir luck ke baad aapko discipline, you can be disciplined only if you're lucky.

03:53:00.380 --> 03:53:09.380
[Guest]: Like if you are really working, you know, 20 hours a day, you can't really, you know, be lucky or you can't really be disciplined.

03:53:09.380 --> 03:53:16.380
[Guest]: Agar aapko writer banna hai, lekin aapka janam hi aise ghar mein hua hai, jahan pe aapke paas kitabe hi nahi hai.

03:53:16.380 --> 03:53:22.380
[Guest]: Mere paas 8 saal, 6 saal ki umar se kitabe aayi. Aur main tab se padh raha hu.

03:53:22.380 --> 03:53:32.380
[Guest]: And I've had a fairly comfortable life in terms of financial access to things and all kinds of language access to things.

03:53:32.380 --> 03:53:39.380
[Guest]: Toh phir maine discipline usme se dhund liya aur main wo kar paya.

03:53:39.380 --> 03:53:49.380
[Guest]: If someone who still wanted to be a writer, first of all, people to get the idea that you can be a writer is also part of my luck.

03:53:49.380 --> 03:54:02.380
[Guest]: Luck of being born in a particular family at a particular time when, you know, and then whatever life path was given to me through, again, multiple factors.

03:54:02.380 --> 03:54:05.380
[Guest]: So all of it is, I think, quite random.

03:54:05.380 --> 03:54:13.380
[Amit Varma]: And the desire to seek patterns also gives us religions and conspiracy theories and so on and so forth.

03:54:13.380 --> 03:54:21.380
[Amit Varma]: Speaking of Bollywood, my sort of second question, because in a sense, you said that, you know, the 90s was a tumultuous decade.

03:54:21.380 --> 03:54:25.380
[Amit Varma]: So much changed in the world, so much progress, analog to digital and all that.

03:54:25.380 --> 03:54:35.380
[Amit Varma]: And I think the current times in terms of what is happening to culture and cinema and all that is also momentous when you think about the pace of change.

03:54:35.380 --> 03:54:45.380
[Amit Varma]: Because what I see happening in different domains in the world and happening less fast in cinema, but also in cinema is what I referred to before the crumbling away of the mainstream.

03:54:45.380 --> 03:54:50.380
[Amit Varma]: Like in media, we have seen ki 1990s mein there was a consensus on the truth broad.

03:54:50.380 --> 03:54:59.380
[Amit Varma]: There were your major publications and there was a lot of negative associated with that also because there were gatekeepers for art and artists and access was controlled.

03:54:59.380 --> 03:55:02.380
[Amit Varma]: And now, of course, there is no consensus on the truth.

03:55:02.380 --> 03:55:04.380
[Amit Varma]: We are engaged in narrative battles all the time.

03:55:04.380 --> 03:55:06.380
[Amit Varma]: That's a negative side of the ledger.

03:55:06.380 --> 03:55:11.380
[Amit Varma]: I would still say the positive side overwhelms that in the sense that all of us have the means of production.

03:55:11.380 --> 03:55:13.380
[Amit Varma]: We don't have to go through gatekeepers.

03:55:13.380 --> 03:55:21.380
[Amit Varma]: We can do crazy things which would never get past a gatekeeper earlier, like five hour podcasts and just keep doing it till we refine what we are doing.

03:55:21.380 --> 03:55:23.380
[Amit Varma]: And the mainstream has kind of crumbled away there.

03:55:23.380 --> 03:55:30.380
[Amit Varma]: We see it, I believe, even in nation states where lines on a map are becoming less relevant in a globalized world.

03:55:30.380 --> 03:55:32.380
[Amit Varma]: And I see it happening everywhere.

03:55:32.380 --> 03:55:41.380
[Amit Varma]: Now, in cinema also, I feel like it is just a matter of time because what you really have coming from, say, any film industry.

03:55:41.380 --> 03:55:48.380
[Amit Varma]: If you look at Bollywood coming from Bombay, you have a film industry run by a few people almost in a central planning kind of way.

03:55:48.380 --> 03:55:50.380
[Amit Varma]: And they don't really get the country.

03:55:50.380 --> 03:55:56.380
[Amit Varma]: They are either kind of driven by narrow business imperatives, but they don't understand the people behind the numbers.

03:55:56.380 --> 03:56:06.380
[Amit Varma]: Or they are, you know, foreign educated kids in elite film families and they've kind of taken over that family business, but they don't get it later either.

03:56:06.380 --> 03:56:13.380
[Amit Varma]: Which is why I love TikTok so much. I thought it was such a tragedy that it was banned because I saw it as such a great platform,

03:56:13.380 --> 03:56:23.380
[Amit Varma]: the kind of art from villages and towns and people of alternate sexualities expressing themselves and seeing other people like themselves where there is no gatekeeper.

03:56:23.380 --> 03:56:29.380
[Amit Varma]: And I thought after that initial phase of, you know, you're going with a meme and you're lip syncing to something,

03:56:29.380 --> 03:56:35.380
[Amit Varma]: after that initial phase, I saw some really cutting edge stuff coming out of there and it's a great tragedy it is in there.

03:56:35.380 --> 03:56:41.380
[Amit Varma]: But in general, when we look at, and I don't even want to say cinema because that feels like it's putting it in a box,

03:56:41.380 --> 03:56:51.380
[Amit Varma]: but that whole, all of audiovisual entertainment, storytelling per se, you know, where do you sort of see the future going?

03:56:51.380 --> 03:56:57.380
[Amit Varma]: And I don't want you to be a forecaster and tell me that this will happen in 2035 and I will be here and all of that.

03:56:57.380 --> 03:57:08.380
[Amit Varma]: But just in general, what are the sort of trends that you see, what worries you, what gives you hope about the way this world is emerging and what excites you as a creator?

03:57:08.380 --> 03:57:16.380
[Guest]: Okay. So yeah, generally, I think as whatever, generally humans are really bad at predicting future.

03:57:16.380 --> 03:57:29.380
[Guest]: And I'm even worse at it because I can't really see, I can't, whatever, my brain kind of collapses when I start thinking, okay, what's going to happen next?

03:57:29.380 --> 03:57:47.380
[Guest]: So, seriously, what excites me is this very fast changing world around us and this clash of multiple centers of power.

03:57:47.380 --> 03:58:04.380
[Guest]: And this very contrasting thing about globalized world and then the rise of right wing, rise of this, you know, xenophobia around the world.

03:58:04.380 --> 03:58:22.380
[Guest]: So, it will be as whatever Chinese say, interesting times. So, that is what kind of excites me that there will be lots to talk about, lots to reflect on, lots to analyze and make sense of.

03:58:22.380 --> 03:58:37.380
[Guest]: Because things are not getting simple. We are kind of getting, no matter, of course, times have always been turbulent and times are always look, they always look more complicated than they were previously.

03:58:37.380 --> 03:58:49.380
[Guest]: But if that is true, and I think that is true, the world is kind of getting more and more complicated because more and more gates have come down around the world.

03:58:49.380 --> 03:58:58.380
[Guest]: And the kind of interactions that are possible now, and that is something which gives me great hope also.

03:58:58.380 --> 03:59:11.380
[Guest]: That this idea that some people in power can restrict what you think or what you eat, that's not possible anymore.

03:59:11.380 --> 03:59:19.380
[Guest]: No matter how much power they put in, no matter what, you know, they can't do anything. I have complete faith in that.

03:59:19.380 --> 03:59:28.380
[Guest]: Because now what has happened, the doors have opened, people have seen a lot of things, you can't take back that power from them.

03:59:28.380 --> 03:59:34.380
[Guest]: Okay, what has not reached them, maybe you can stop it, some things, some ideas.

03:59:34.380 --> 03:59:47.380
[Guest]: But what has reached them, and they are too many, the ideas that have reached people, the idea of expressing the free expression, that has reached people.

03:59:47.380 --> 03:59:59.380
[Guest]: And that is something which is now very difficult. You can probably control, which is what they will try to say, that you can say things, but say this particular thing.

03:59:59.380 --> 04:00:06.380
[Guest]: But to convince people that you can't say anything, that is not going to happen.

04:00:06.380 --> 04:00:09.380
[Guest]: So that gives me great hope because this has happened.

04:00:09.380 --> 04:00:23.380
[Guest]: Okay, internet has been a great tool for the powerful people around the world in polarizing and pushing down their agenda very quickly and very effectively.

04:00:23.380 --> 04:00:33.380
[Guest]: But at the same time, they don't understand that right now, the medium itself is a bigger message than the message they are giving.

04:00:33.380 --> 04:00:42.380
[Guest]: And the medium is getting empowered, the medium of quick, effective communication, that medium has reached people.

04:00:42.380 --> 04:00:57.380
[Guest]: And that means everyone will at some point find their voice and find their cause and find through the clutter or through the orders that this is what we want to say.

04:00:57.380 --> 04:01:08.380
[Guest]: And we will say it because we have the medium and that medium is free and that medium is free to whatever, with all the caveats around the word free.

04:01:08.380 --> 04:01:14.380
[Guest]: But that is generally a hopeful thing for me.

04:01:14.380 --> 04:01:29.380
[Guest]: And secondly, as a writer, it is very exciting to make sense of these things and to find stories that kind of become a symbol of this clash, which we are seeing around us.

04:01:29.380 --> 04:01:41.380
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, so you know, we've kind of come to the end of our allotted time, but I'm going to hopefully, if there's a listener demand, you will come back for a part two at some point, maybe when your film is out.

04:01:41.380 --> 04:01:50.380
[Amit Varma]: Because I wanted to talk about your time in comedy, the craft of comedy, the craft of writing lyrics, the craft of writing screenplays, and much more about cinema.

04:01:50.380 --> 04:01:57.380
[Amit Varma]: Because hopefully, by the time your next recording with me, you'll be, you know, your directorial debut will be out also.

04:01:57.380 --> 04:01:59.380
[Amit Varma]: So I'm really excited about that.

04:01:59.380 --> 04:02:11.380
[Amit Varma]: But my last question, and this is a question I ask all my guests, particularly interesting with you is, can you recommend books, films, music that have meant a lot to you at an emotional level?

04:02:11.380 --> 04:02:17.380
[Amit Varma]: Like the kind of things you take to a desert island, that cliched question, or the kind of things you want to stand in a soapbox and you want to tell the world,

04:02:17.380 --> 04:02:27.380
[Guest]: can the world's boss read this or watch this or listen to this?

04:02:27.380 --> 04:02:47.380
[Guest]: That's also a bit of a problem, but maybe top of my mind, whatever comes to mind, I'll keep talking about it. So music, the golden age of Hindi cinema music is the 50s and 60s till mid 70s kind of a thing.

04:02:47.380 --> 04:02:59.380
[Guest]: The music of the 70s has been a very defining part of my life. Because of that, I have learned lyrics writing.

04:02:59.380 --> 04:03:11.380
[Guest]: I have learned through it and it has been so much in my mind and heart since childhood that that's something which pushes me to do better as a lyrics writer.

04:03:11.380 --> 04:03:23.380
[Guest]: Because a lot of people say, it's a general belief, it's not wrong, that poetry was very good at that time.

04:03:23.380 --> 04:03:33.380
[Guest]: But a lot of people don't understand and don't realize how that music is still alive.

04:03:33.380 --> 04:03:43.380
[Guest]: There may be a lot of people who don't recognize how SD Burman used to look or this song is by SD Burman or Shankar Jayakrishnan or C Ramchandra.

04:03:43.380 --> 04:03:54.380
[Guest]: It may be difficult for people to tell, but the music has survived and music has persisted. And in many cases, it has grown in value and impact.

04:03:54.380 --> 04:04:06.380
[Guest]: But what a lot of people don't realize is that not only the quality of the poetry was not good, but the technical aspect was also very correct.

04:04:06.380 --> 04:04:20.380
[Guest]: So the meter of the song, the phrasing of the song at that time, there is a meter, which is an English understanding of meter, which comes from Western music or Western poetry.

04:04:20.380 --> 04:04:28.380
[Guest]: But Hindi film music is a very unique form of music in itself.

04:04:28.380 --> 04:04:48.380
[Guest]: I feel it should be treated as a very well-defined, respected genre of music as like Carnatic music or Hindustani classical or Western music or jazz or any other form of music which we consider to be a respected genre.

04:04:48.380 --> 04:04:54.380
[Guest]: So Hindi film music is a very unique form of music in itself.

04:04:54.380 --> 04:05:00.380
[Guest]: It has all kinds of musical influences. That's fine. That's a different part of history. I'm just talking about poetry.

04:05:00.380 --> 04:05:21.380
[Guest]: For this, if a tune has been given, now this is the tune, on which the lyrics of Gaata Rahe Mera Dil have been written, it will only be in the minds of people that only the words have been paid attention to, that Gaata Rahe Mera Dil.

04:05:21.380 --> 04:05:33.380
[Guest]: But when the poet has written it, then the mouth will open twice in Gaata, then it will not open in Rahe, then it will open on Mera and it will not open in Dil.

04:05:33.380 --> 04:05:51.380
[Guest]: That understanding is also there embedded in the music of 50s, 60s and 70s. The understanding of what the exact phrasing for that particular tune is and how that tune will be enhanced by this phrasing.

04:05:51.380 --> 04:06:06.380
[Guest]: And instead of Gaata Rahe Mera Dil, you can also write Haasta Rahe Mera Dil in the meter. And it will sit, it will almost sit. Haasta Rahe Mera Dil or Jeeta Rahe Mera Dil.

04:06:06.380 --> 04:06:24.380
[Guest]: But because of Gaata Rahe Mera Dil, the beauty of that song increases, which takes the poetry of that time to a different level, which again is part of the poetry but not the front of it.

04:06:24.380 --> 04:06:37.380
[Guest]: People only, you know, if you get into the technicals of it, then you'll understand. So for me, that era is a very emotional attachment, but just as a lyrics writer to be part of that legacy,

04:06:37.380 --> 04:06:48.380
[Guest]: it kind of keeps telling me to not be frivolous about it, to always be very, very sure of what you write and what you put out.

04:06:48.380 --> 04:07:04.380
[Guest]: So all the music of that era, I would say, if anyone wants to listen to new music or those who have listened to it a little, they can interact with it very carefully and very well.

04:07:04.380 --> 04:07:20.380
[Guest]: Then there is another Punjabi music, which is probably from the 70s, 80s, the era of Surinder Kaur and Asa Singh Mastana and then the Pakistani music of that time,

04:07:20.380 --> 04:07:30.380
[Guest]: which was Mehdi Hasan and Ghulam Ali and Nusrat Saheb and Parveen Sultana and you know, Noor Jahan and all.

04:07:30.380 --> 04:07:54.380
[Guest]: So there is that again, that strange connection to a home you have not seen, but you have been told that was our home and there is connection to that land,

04:07:54.380 --> 04:08:01.380
[Guest]: to that culture, to that language and you kind of want to connect to that in some ways.

04:08:01.380 --> 04:08:14.380
[Guest]: And in spite of all the political divides that exist and have been constantly nurtured by both the governments,

04:08:14.380 --> 04:08:30.380
[Guest]: in spite of that, you kind of want to transcend that border and reach those people and reach that language and music and whatever can come to us,

04:08:30.380 --> 04:08:46.380
[Guest]: food and all other things cannot reach us, food and clothes. So that is another, maybe one of the forever ones of my life. So that collection again, I can't choose anything like particular,

04:08:46.380 --> 04:09:00.380
[Guest]: but all the artists who have been there. Thirdly, in cinema, it's mostly, I would say, Iranian cinema, which has really, really influenced me,

04:09:00.380 --> 04:09:09.380
[Guest]: which I consider to be the most transformative and then the cinema of Satyajit Ray, which again, you used to listen to it for a while,

04:09:09.380 --> 04:09:20.380
[Guest]: Satyajit Ray is great and it had been said many times, so it was getting more and more that you had seen and you did not understand,

04:09:20.380 --> 04:09:32.380
[Guest]: so basically you are a fool. So because of that, I stayed away for a long time, I did not see and whatever little snatches I saw,

04:09:32.380 --> 04:09:46.380
[Guest]: they were on badly, you know, whatever preserved DVDs of his initial films, the Upoot Trilogy. So it was very bad, so I got scared,

04:09:46.380 --> 04:09:55.380
[Guest]: that I don't know, I will have to put a lot of effort to understand this, but then at some point I kind of overcame that fear.

04:09:55.380 --> 04:10:06.380
[Guest]: And then the cinema that I got to see, that is something which gave me immense confidence in telling our stories,

04:10:06.380 --> 04:10:17.380
[Guest]: telling our stories in whatever, you know, whatever level of craft we know and then at some point that, as I said,

04:10:17.380 --> 04:10:27.380
[Guest]: aesthetic is its own, you know, authenticity is its own aesthetic. So trust in that part that, okay, as long as you are authentic,

04:10:27.380 --> 04:10:38.380
[Guest]: craft will take care of its own. So that will happen. You just have to go in authenticity and that's what I think Mr. Ray and his cinema

04:10:38.380 --> 04:10:48.380
[Guest]: kind of taught me and especially the Upoot Trilogy and then the Calcutta Trilogy. These were two.

04:10:48.380 --> 04:10:56.380
[Guest]: And then how he kind of, his last film also, Aagantuk, jo ek cheez hum dekhte hain generally ki after a point,

04:10:56.380 --> 04:11:04.380
[Guest]: most of the creators kind of have a burnout or kind of lose interest or kind of take things for granted,

04:11:04.380 --> 04:11:15.380
[Guest]: but it was like to see that film and to know ki ye unki aakhari film hai, which is, I think, true for a lot of great artists.

04:11:15.380 --> 04:11:24.380
[Guest]: The last work they have created is really impactful, is something where it kind of looks like they knew this is their last work.

04:11:24.380 --> 04:11:36.380
[Guest]: And sometimes they do know and sometimes they don't, like Miyazaki's last film, The Wind Rises, again, has that quality of someone

04:11:36.380 --> 04:11:46.380
[Guest]: very clearly like writing the last chapter of their autobiography or, you know, last. So it's very clear.

04:11:46.380 --> 04:11:54.380
[Guest]: This is what they want the world to kind of think about them and their work and how they have interacted with the world,

04:11:54.380 --> 04:12:12.380
[Guest]: which is very, very clear in Satyajit Ray's last work also. And that just the entire filmography of Mr. Ray.

04:12:12.380 --> 04:12:22.380
[Guest]: That has not just inspired me in a, whatever, in an artistic manner, ki okay, this is the kind of artist I aspire to be and all.

04:12:22.380 --> 04:12:32.380
[Guest]: But generally how to, like again, how to just interact with the world on a day-to-day basis and stay curious forever,

04:12:32.380 --> 04:12:40.380
[Guest]: forever you can afford to. Of course, at some point the health will take over and probably can't stay curious enough

04:12:40.380 --> 04:12:56.380
[Guest]: about things outside of yourself. But again, I would say then there are, of course, snatches of world cinema.

04:12:56.380 --> 04:13:11.380
[Guest]: There's some French film and then say Michael Hennecke has been really serious, I mean, influence and someone who is very, very impressive.

04:13:11.380 --> 04:13:23.380
[Guest]: Or Kieslowski, again, another great artist who is just so involved in the characters and in the stories

04:13:23.380 --> 04:13:33.380
[Guest]: and always finding the humanity in people, no matter what, you know, how, how, how, whatever.

04:13:33.380 --> 04:13:40.380
[Guest]: For me, Decalogue is like just a peak of filmmaking. Absolutely. Absolutely. Decalogue and The Three Colors.

04:13:40.380 --> 04:13:45.380
[Guest]: And then there are other, these some of his other works, which are outside of Decalogue,

04:13:45.380 --> 04:13:51.380
[Guest]: which were kind of the full length features out of Decalogue. Those two films, short film about killing and love.

04:13:51.380 --> 04:14:01.380
[Guest]: And so all of that is, it just creates a new, you know, it's not just almost like it's not a new aesthetic.

04:14:01.380 --> 04:14:09.380
[Guest]: It's a new form of filmmaking, which he created with those, you know, with his very, it's not a big body of work he has created.

04:14:09.380 --> 04:14:14.380
[Guest]: And still it is so impactful. So these are some of the people I would say.

04:14:14.380 --> 04:14:21.380
[Guest]: Then books. I have read a lot of Hindi. I have read less English.

04:14:21.380 --> 04:14:28.380
[Guest]: Whatever I have read, again, because I have not read a lot, I do not have that much distinction.

04:14:28.380 --> 04:14:37.380
[Guest]: But the book that influenced me the most in the beginning, the English book, was Arundhati Roy's God of Small Things.

04:14:37.380 --> 04:14:45.380
[Guest]: The first time I read it, I just, I was blown away that this kind of poetry is possible in English.

04:14:45.380 --> 04:14:52.380
[Guest]: I have read a lot of poetry and poetic books in Hindi, in which almost the language is flowing like poetry.

04:14:52.380 --> 04:15:04.380
[Guest]: From Dharamveer Bharti to Harishankar Parsai's Satyar, or Shrilal Shukla's Raag Darbari, or Uday Prakash, one of the recent, I would say, recent greats.

04:15:04.380 --> 04:15:16.380
[Guest]: There have been two periods in Hindi, in a way, I think, a pre-70s generation, which were all the legends of Hindi literature and even Urdu literature of those times.

04:15:16.380 --> 04:15:28.380
[Guest]: And then there was a lull almost, post-70s, there have been very few, but 70s to 2000s is one period where, you know, Uday Prakash was there.

04:15:28.380 --> 04:15:54.380
[Guest]: Then there is that post Chetan Bhagat generation, which is the new, you know, new wave of Hindi literature, which is very, kind of after Chetan Bhagat, kind of, you know, showed the world that these very simple stories about concerns of the modern youth can kind of have a market value.

04:15:54.380 --> 04:16:02.380
[Guest]: And then after that, there was a new period in Hindi, in which today's writers are Satya Vyas and Nikhil Sachan.

04:16:02.380 --> 04:16:11.380
[Guest]: So, that is a different period, I have not read that much and I mean, I cannot relate to it.

04:16:11.380 --> 04:16:21.380
[Guest]: But in pre-70s, Manohar Shyam Joshi is someone, I am like constantly amazed by his writing.

04:16:21.380 --> 04:16:29.380
[Guest]: Nayyar Masood is one Urdu writer, whom I recently discovered some 2-3 years ago.

04:16:29.380 --> 04:16:40.380
[Guest]: And I do not think that in the whole world, if you make a list of top 5 short stories, of course, it is a very subjective kind of a thing.

04:16:40.380 --> 04:16:45.380
[Guest]: But short story, oh wow, Nayyar Masood Sahib.

04:16:45.380 --> 04:16:48.380
[Guest]: So, this is a collection of his short stories.

04:16:48.380 --> 04:16:51.380
[Guest]: English collection, yeah, collected short stories of his.

04:16:51.380 --> 04:16:55.380
[Guest]: So, if you can read him in Hindi, it will be amazing.

04:16:55.380 --> 04:16:58.380
[Unknown]: I do not know how much it will be translated.

04:16:58.380 --> 04:17:03.380
[Guest]: But again, I think you will get the impact, at least just the craft of it.

04:17:03.380 --> 04:17:10.380
[Guest]: And because weaving a short story is a very, very delicate craft.

04:17:10.380 --> 04:17:18.380
[Guest]: So, I read Nayyar Masood Sahib and suddenly, I mean, all the short stories I have read,

04:17:18.380 --> 04:17:23.380
[Guest]: they all became one and then Nayyar Masood came in front.

04:17:23.380 --> 04:17:29.380
[Guest]: Because he was, I think, at some point he was translating a lot of Kafka into Urdu.

04:17:29.380 --> 04:17:43.380
[Guest]: So, he has that, whatever that eye for abstract and weird and bizarre and still has that language of the Lucknow ki ek bahuti sundar si zabaan.

04:17:43.380 --> 04:17:52.380
[Guest]: Aur phir us zabaan ke jo details hain aur phir us world ke jo details hain Lucknow ke jo unhone dekha hai 50s, 60s, 70s ka shayad.

04:17:52.380 --> 04:17:57.380
[Guest]: Khas kar gaya, I think, 60s to 80s wala jo daur tha Lucknow ka.

04:17:57.380 --> 04:18:05.380
[Guest]: Toh Nayyar Masood hain, unki wajah se maine actually one of the reasons I learnt reading Urdu

04:18:05.380 --> 04:18:09.380
[Guest]: because unki bahut kam kahaniyan Hindi mein translate hui hain.

04:18:09.380 --> 04:18:14.380
[Guest]: Aur Hindi mein hoti hain toh phir bhi bahut saare Urdu lafz rehte hain usme.

04:18:14.380 --> 04:18:18.380
[Guest]: Lekin, toh isliye Hindi mein padhne mein maza aata hai.

04:18:18.380 --> 04:18:25.380
[Guest]: But phir bhi maine socha ki original Urdu mein jo likha hai aur bahut saari kahaniyan jo ussi mein hain abhi bhi exist karti hain,

04:18:25.380 --> 04:18:27.380
[Guest]: jo abhi tak translate bhi nahi hui hain.

04:18:27.380 --> 04:18:31.380
[Guest]: So, Nayyar Masood is another great writer.

04:18:31.380 --> 04:18:35.380
[Guest]: I am very, very blessed to read.

04:18:35.380 --> 04:18:38.380
[Guest]: And then Shams-ur-Rehman Faruqi sahab.

04:18:38.380 --> 04:18:41.380
[Guest]: Again, another...

04:18:41.380 --> 04:18:52.380
[Guest]: Madhav unko sirf writer kehna, he was one of the, I think, greatest critics and observer of language and culture

04:18:52.380 --> 04:18:59.380
[Guest]: aur jo unka interpretation jo raha hai, poetry ka, Ghalib ka, Akbar-e-Ilaabadi ka

04:18:59.380 --> 04:19:04.380
[Guest]: ya aur Urdu kya jo bhi ek pura culture raha hai, Urdu literary world ka.

04:19:04.380 --> 04:19:07.380
[Guest]: So, he has constantly been...

04:19:07.380 --> 04:19:17.380
[Guest]: He was constantly adding more insights and layers to our understanding of what they have achieved in that world.

04:19:17.380 --> 04:19:23.380
[Guest]: Aur unka phir abhi recently jo, recently mein log kuch time ho gaya hai, khair, maine recently padha hai,

04:19:23.380 --> 04:19:27.380
[Guest]: Kahi Chaan The Sar-e-Asma, that novel,

04:19:27.380 --> 04:19:37.380
[Guest]: jo ki ek toh itna ghazab ka premise hai, uska about just Daag-Dehlvi jo Urdu ke shayar rahe.

04:19:37.380 --> 04:19:44.380
[Guest]: Unka lineage unhone kuch 600-700 saal ki kahaani hain.

04:19:44.380 --> 04:19:50.380
[Guest]: 600-700 saal ki aur 400-500 saal, kam se kam 500 saal ki, before the British era.

04:19:50.380 --> 04:19:58.380
[Guest]: And wahaan se unki lineage trace karte karte, har generation ki kahaani hain aur kis tare se wo yahaan tak pauche,

04:19:58.380 --> 04:20:01.380
[Guest]: jahaan pe finally we come to Daag-Dehlvi.

04:20:01.380 --> 04:20:06.380
[Guest]: But it's the story of Daag-Dehlvi, actually the central character is Daag-Dehlvi's mother.

04:20:06.380 --> 04:20:12.380
[Guest]: But unke upar jaate jaate kahaniya, itni saari kahaniya usme khulti jaate hain aur har kahani,

04:20:12.380 --> 04:20:19.380
[Guest]: har page main kai-kai baar padhta hoon, kyunki har description khubsurat hai aur har description.

04:20:19.380 --> 04:20:31.380
[Guest]: And it's a, at some points you think, okay, it's not a, it is not fiction because a lot of it is actually oral history of that family.

04:20:31.380 --> 04:20:38.380
[Guest]: But then at most of the points, it is just an anthropological study of those times and cultures.

04:20:38.380 --> 04:20:43.380
[Guest]: Jab wo kapdon ki baat karte hain, toh wo 2-3 page main wo kapda banta kaise tha,

04:20:43.380 --> 04:20:49.380
[Guest]: kaunsi cheez usme kahaan se aati thi, kaise weaving process kya tha, rang kahaan se aata tha,

04:20:49.380 --> 04:20:54.380
[Guest]: aur phir wo moti kahaan se aate the, aur kis tare se usko pehna jaata tha, kis tare se usko dhoya jaata tha.

04:20:54.380 --> 04:21:00.380
[Guest]: 2-3 page uspe hain, phir koi khaani ki agar baat ho rahi hai, toh phir wo recipe kahaan se chalke wahaan tak aayi thi,

04:21:00.380 --> 04:21:05.380
[Guest]: aur kaise wo banti hai, aur kaise usko khaate hain, aur agar wo zyada khalo toh bimaar ho jao,

04:21:05.380 --> 04:21:12.380
[Guest]: toh phir uska ilaaj kya hai, us tare ki bahut saari galiyon mein wo leke jaate hain,

04:21:12.380 --> 04:21:17.380
[Guest]: aur us tare ki koi cheez maine kabhi padhi hi nahi hain.

04:21:17.380 --> 04:21:23.380
[Guest]: Us tare ka koi novel, I don't think, exist karta hai duniya mein, where it is as much a novel,

04:21:23.380 --> 04:21:30.380
[Guest]: as a historical document, as an anthropological study, as just whatever,

04:21:30.380 --> 04:21:38.380
[Guest]: as an encyclopedia of a particular time period in a particular kind of family,

04:21:38.380 --> 04:21:45.380
[Guest]: just encyclopedia about everything from customs to clothing to food.

04:21:45.380 --> 04:21:51.380
[Guest]: Toh yeh kuch cheezein hain jo bahut pasand hain, jo top of my mind maine boli.

04:21:51.380 --> 04:21:57.380
[Guest]: Uske alawa, of course, there are thousand other things which I can't really think of right now.

04:21:57.380 --> 04:22:00.380
[Amit Varma]: Thanks a lot for these. And just for the listeners, a brief interruption,

04:22:00.380 --> 04:22:07.380
[Amit Varma]: when Varun was mentioning Nair Masood Sahib, as I happen to have an English translation of his collected stories on my desk,

04:22:07.380 --> 04:22:12.380
[Amit Varma]: so he kind of spotted that. And this also happened a few episodes ago, I think in December,

04:22:12.380 --> 04:22:17.380
[Amit Varma]: I had Sara Rai, who's very fine writer, granddaughter of Munshi Premchand, but a very fine writer, you should read her.

04:22:17.380 --> 04:22:23.380
[Amit Varma]: So she had also mentioned Nair Masood and then she spotted the book, which was on the shelf at that time.

04:22:23.380 --> 04:22:29.380
[Amit Varma]: And you mentioned last films, and you know, that's very interesting, like Louis Buuel's last three films, for example,

04:22:29.380 --> 04:22:34.380
[Amit Varma]: which he made in the 70s, or John Huston made The Dead, which was based on the James Joyce short story,

04:22:34.380 --> 04:22:39.380
[Amit Varma]: which is so moving. One of those films that really made a mark on me.

04:22:39.380 --> 04:22:45.380
[Amit Varma]: And I was also struck by, you know, what you said about Ray, that it was more than a cinema.

04:22:45.380 --> 04:22:49.380
[Amit Varma]: And I think I know what you mean, that it was more than the aesthetic.

04:22:49.380 --> 04:22:54.380
[Amit Varma]: It's also the ethic of engaging with the world in the way that he did till his last days.

04:22:54.380 --> 04:23:01.380
[Amit Varma]: And that's also an ethic that I clearly, you know, see in you as well, in your work.

04:23:01.380 --> 04:23:06.380
[Amit Varma]: So hoping for more conversations and, you know, to see much more of your work.

04:23:06.380 --> 04:23:11.380
[Amit Varma]: Thank you so much, boss. You've, you know, spent quite a few hours. There's been a fire outside.

